-- ============================================================
-- Booklesss — Treasury Management step content seed
-- Run in Supabase SQL Editor AFTER seed_lessons_steps.sql.
--
-- Populates the `content` JSONB for all 10 built Treasury Management
-- steps, transcribed from the ReportLab build scripts in
-- Schools/ZCAS/Treasury Management/*/sources/build_tm_*.py (and the
-- legacy build_lesson_1_1_tm.py for step 1.1) — the source of truth per
-- CLAUDE.md, since all text lives directly in the script.
--
-- Note: Step 1.1's source script predates the two-discussion-question
-- convention and has none embedded verbatim — its two discussion questions
-- here were written to be faithful to the step's actual content (cost vs
-- profit centre, the Nick Leeson/Barings case, strategic/tactical/
-- operational classification) rather than lifted from the PDF text.
--
-- Tables and formulas from the PDFs are folded into readable prose in
-- `body` since the StepContent JSON schema (platform/lib/types.ts) has no
-- table/formula type. Inline PDF markup (<b>, <i>, <br/>) is stripped
-- since LessonContent.tsx renders section body as plain text, not HTML.
-- ============================================================

update steps set content = '{"sections": [{"eyebrow": "FOUNDATIONS", "heading": "What is Treasury?", "body": "Treasury is the financial centre of an organisation. Its core job is to protect the company''s financial assets, manage its liabilities, and make sure cash is available when it''s needed.\n\nDay-to-day, that means keeping suppliers paid, meeting debt obligations, and ensuring surplus cash earns rather than sits idle. The treasury team executes decisions made by senior management — they don''t set strategy, they carry it out. And they have a major role in identifying and reducing financial risk.", "callout": {"label": "Fact", "body": "The structure of a treasury department varies by company size, industry, and organisational complexity."}}, {"eyebrow": "CORE CONCEPTS", "heading": "The Three Finance Decisions", "body": "Every finance function operates within three broad decision areas.\n\n1. Investment Decision. How does the company deploy its available resources? This covers long-term project commitments, working capital investment (stock, debtors), and internal or external investment decisions.\n\n2. Financing Decision. How does the company raise the money it needs? This means finding the right mix of debt and equity, understanding the cost of funds, managing capital structure, and handling risk and hedging.\n\n3. Dividend Policy. What happens to profits? How much is paid out to shareholders and how much is retained to fund growth. Dividend levels directly affect the company''s market value."}, {"eyebrow": "SCOPE", "heading": "The 11 Main Functions of Treasury", "body": "The treasurer''s responsibilities go well beyond holding cash. The eleven main functions are: 1) Cash forecasting — pulls short and long-term forecasts from all subsidiaries. 2) Working capital management — monitors working capital levels and trends. 3) Cash management — keeps sufficient cash available for operations at all times. 4) Investment management — invests surplus cash appropriately. 5) Risk management — manages interest rate and FX exposure. 6) Management advice — advises leadership on market conditions. 7) Credit rating relations — liaises with agencies when issuing marketable debt. 8) Bank relationships — manages banking fees, terms, and ongoing communications. 9) Fund raising — maintains investor relationships for capital raising. 10) Credit granting — grants credit to customers on behalf of the business. 11) Other activities — M&A support, company insurance, and similar matters."}, {"eyebrow": "TASK LEVELS", "heading": "Strategic, Tactical & Operational", "body": "Treasury work happens at three levels. Knowing which is which matters in the exam.\n\nStrategic level focuses on long-term policy, with examples such as capital structure, dividend policy, capital raising, and investment returns.\n\nTactical level focuses on medium-term decisions, such as cash investment management and hedging currency or interest rate risk.\n\nOperational level focuses on daily execution, such as transmitting cash, placing surplus funds, and bank communications.", "callout": {"label": "Note", "body": "Exam tip: classify by time horizon. Strategic = long-term policy. Tactical = medium-term decisions. Operational = daily execution."}}, {"eyebrow": "STRUCTURE", "heading": "Cost Centre vs Profit Centre", "body": "How a company classifies its treasury function changes how it''s managed and measured.\n\nCost Centre (Most Common). Treasury is treated as a support function — not expected to generate profit, just manage costs. The risk here is that management fixates on what treasury costs rather than what it contributes, which can starve the function of budget and staff.\n\nProfit Centre. Used by companies heavily involved in global finance, FX trading, or commodities. Treasury actively generates income through trading, hedging, or internal service pricing.\n\nAs a profit centre, the advantages are that business units pay market rates so cost transparency improves, and the treasurer is incentivised to operate efficiently. The disadvantages are the temptation to speculate, internal disputes over charges, and higher admin costs.", "callout": {"label": "Warning", "body": "Nick Leeson at Barings Bank (1995) is the exam case. He ran treasury-style operations with no oversight, hid losses in a secret account, and brought down the bank. The lesson: unchecked profit-centre thinking without controls is catastrophic."}}, {"eyebrow": "CONTROLS", "heading": "Treasury Controls", "body": "Because treasury handles large sums, controls are non-negotiable. Six to know.\n\n1. Segregation of Duties. Front office (dealing/trading) must be separate from back office (confirmation and settlement). No one person initiates and confirms their own transactions.\n\n2. Delegation of Authority. The right level of decision-making must sit with the right people. High-risk decisions require senior sign-off; routine ones should not.\n\n3. Limits. Caps on transaction size, type, or instrument. Prevents staff from investing in instruments with excessive risk of capital loss.\n\n4. Approvals. All trades approved by a senior manager. A separate person reconciles and accounts for every transaction.\n\n5. Internal Audits. Scheduled audits match actual transactions against company policy — catching drift before it becomes a problem.\n\n6. Automation / STP. Straight-Through Processing removes manual steps from routine transactions, reducing errors and fraud opportunities."}, {"eyebrow": "STRUCTURE", "heading": "Centralised, Decentralised & Hybrid", "body": "How treasury is structured geographically depends on how the business operates.\n\nCentralised: all operations run from HQ. Advantage — stronger controls, economies of scale, lower costs, tax advantages for MNCs. Disadvantage — field offices lose autonomy and local knowledge is not captured.\n\nDecentralised: subsidiaries manage their own treasury under group guidelines. Advantage — local staff know local banking, regulations, language and customs. Disadvantage — duplication of effort and resources across units.\n\nHybrid: regional centres — centralised within regions, decentralised across them. Advantage — combines central control with local knowledge. Disadvantage — more complex to set up and manage.", "callout": {"label": "Fact", "body": "The hybrid model is increasingly common. Modern Treasury Management Systems allow local teams to input data centrally — giving HQ oversight without removing local responsiveness."}}], "keyTerms": [{"term": "Treasury", "definition": "The function responsible for managing an organisation''s financial assets, liabilities, and cash"}, {"term": "Cost centre", "definition": "A department measured by costs incurred, not profits generated"}, {"term": "Profit centre", "definition": "A department expected to generate income through trading or internal pricing"}, {"term": "Segregation of duties", "definition": "Splitting trading and confirmation roles between different staff to prevent fraud"}, {"term": "Delegation of authority", "definition": "Assigning decision-making power to appropriate levels within the treasury team"}, {"term": "STP", "definition": "Straight-Through Processing — automated transaction processing with no manual intervention"}, {"term": "Centralised treasury", "definition": "All treasury operations managed from a single location, typically HQ"}, {"term": "Decentralised treasury", "definition": "Subsidiaries manage their own treasury within group-wide guidelines"}, {"term": "Hybrid treasury", "definition": "Regional centres combining aspects of centralised and decentralised structures"}], "discussionQuestions": ["A mid-sized Zambian manufacturer is deciding whether to run treasury as a cost centre or a profit centre as it starts trading FX to cover import payments. Which structure would you recommend, and what controls would you put in place to prevent the kind of unchecked risk-taking that brought down Barings Bank?", "Classify each of the following as strategic, tactical, or operational: setting the company''s long-term capital structure, hedging a six-month FX exposure on an import order, and transmitting a supplier payment due tomorrow. Explain the time horizon that puts each one in its category."], "learningOutcomes": ["Define the treasury function and explain its role within an organisation", "Classify treasury activities as strategic, tactical, or operational", "Compare cost centre and profit centre structures, with advantages and disadvantages of each", "List the six main treasury controls and explain why segregation of duties matters", "Distinguish between centralised, decentralised, and hybrid treasury structures"]}'::jsonb
where slug = 'introduction'
  and lesson_id = (select id from lessons where slug = 'operations' and course_id = (select id from courses where slug = 'treasury-management'));

update steps set content = '{"sections": [{"eyebrow": "FOUNDATIONS", "heading": "What is Working Capital?", "body": "Working capital is current assets minus current liabilities. That''s the technical definition. In practice, it''s the pool of cash and near-cash resources a business has available to keep running day-to-day.\n\nIf current assets exceed current liabilities, the company has a surplus — usually sitting in bank deposits or short-term investments. If liabilities exceed assets, there''s a deficit, and the company is typically running on an overdraft or short-term loan.\n\nTreasury''s job is to manage this pool as efficiently as possible. Too little working capital and the business can''t pay its suppliers. Too much and money sits idle earning nothing when it could be in productive assets.", "callout": {"label": "Warning", "body": "Even a profitable business can fail without adequate working capital. Cash is king — not profit. A company can be profitable on paper and still collapse if it can''t meet its near-term obligations."}}, {"eyebrow": "STRATEGY", "heading": "Working Capital Policy", "body": "Every company makes two decisions that together define its working capital policy.\n\n1. The Investment Decision — how much to hold. Companies must hold minimum levels of cash and inventory to keep operations running. The question is: how much safety stock on top of that minimum?\n\nThree investment policy options: An aggressive policy means minimal safety stock — lean inventory and tight cash buffers — giving higher return (less idle capital) but higher risk (can''t respond to demand spikes). A conservative policy means large safety stocks and generous cash buffers, giving lower return (more capital tied up) but lower risk (rarely caught short). A moderate policy is a balanced approach between the two extremes, landing in the middle on both return and risk.\n\n2. The Financing Decision — how to fund it. This is about the mix of short-term vs long-term debt used to finance the asset base.\n\nThree financing policy options: An aggressive policy funds part of the permanent asset base with short-term debt, giving the highest return (short-term debt costs less) but the highest risk (must be rolled over). A conservative policy funds permanent assets with long-term debt only, giving the lowest return and the lowest risk. A maturity matching policy matches funding maturity to asset life, landing in the middle on both return and risk.", "callout": {"label": "Exam Tip", "body": "In both decisions, aggressive = higher return AND higher risk. Conservative = lower return AND lower risk. Always state both sides when the exam asks you to evaluate a policy."}}, {"eyebrow": "MEASUREMENT", "heading": "The Cash Conversion Cycle", "body": "The operating cycle is the time between paying cash for inputs and receiving cash from sales. The cash conversion cycle (CCC) measures this precisely: CCC = Days Inventory + Days Receivables — Days Payables, where Days Inventory = (Inventory ÷ Cost of Goods Sold) × 365, Days Receivables = (Accounts Receivable ÷ Revenue) × 365, and Days Payables = (Accounts Payable ÷ Cost of Goods Sold) × 365.\n\nThe longer the CCC, the more working capital the business needs to fund. A company with a 90-day CCC has to finance 90 days of operations before cash comes in.\n\nWorked Example — Zanaco Distributors Ltd. The company''s figures: Inventory K2,600,000, Accounts Receivable K1,700,000, Accounts Payable K1,600,000, Annual Revenue K15,000,000, Cost of Goods Sold K9,200,000.\n\nStep 1: Days Inventory = (K2,600,000 ÷ K9,200,000) × 365 = 103.15 days. Step 2: Days Receivables = (K1,700,000 ÷ K15,000,000) × 365 = 41.37 days. Step 3: Days Payables = (K1,600,000 ÷ K9,200,000) × 365 = 63.48 days. CCC = 103.15 + 41.37 — 63.48 = 81.04 days. Cash Turnover = 365 ÷ 81.04 = 4.5 times per year.\n\nZanaco Distributors takes just over 81 days from paying for goods to collecting cash. Cash turns over 4.5 times a year. Shortening any component — collecting faster, turning inventory quicker, paying suppliers later — directly reduces funding requirements.\n\nSteps to Shorten the CCC: collect debts faster by reducing debtor days through tighter credit terms or discounts; turn inventory faster by reducing stock holding periods and production time; reduce raw material inventory by ordering more frequently in smaller quantities; and negotiate longer supplier credit to extend payable days without damaging relationships."}, {"eyebrow": "DEBTORS", "heading": "Debtor Management & Credit Control", "body": "Extending credit to customers ties up cash. The goal is to find the level of credit and discount terms that maximises profit — not just minimises days outstanding.\n\nGood credit management involves assessing which customers to extend credit to, setting individual limits, and having a clear process for overdue accounts.\n\nAssessing a Customer''s Creditworthiness draws on several sources: bank references, since Zambian banks provide references on their customers; trade references, where existing suppliers can confirm payment history; published accounts, since annual reports indicate general financial health; the Credit Reference Bureau, Zambia''s credit registry which holds borrowing data across banks; and own sales records, where for existing customers the sales ledger shows payment patterns.\n\nCash Discounts — Cost to the Buyer. Credit terms like ''2/10 net 30'' mean: take a 2% discount if you pay within 10 days, or pay the full amount by day 30. The buyer has to decide whether the discount is worth it. The annual cost of NOT taking the discount is calculated as Cost = [D ÷ (100 - D)] × [365 ÷ (N - T)], where D is the discount percentage, N is the net period, and T is the discount period.\n\nWorked Example — 2/10 net 30. A buyer is offered terms 2/10 net 30. Short-term borrowing rate is 8%. Should they take the discount? Cost = [2 ÷ (100 - 2)] × [365 ÷ (30 - 10)] = 0.0204 × 18.25 = 37.23% per annum. Borrowing cost is 8% p.a. Decision: borrow at 8% and take the discount — forgoing it costs 37.23%.", "callout": {"label": "Note", "body": "Always compare the annual cost of forgoing the discount against the cost of short-term borrowing. If borrowing is cheaper, take the discount. 37.23% vs 8% makes this a straightforward call."}}, {"eyebrow": "OUTSOURCING", "heading": "Factoring vs Invoice Discounting", "body": "Rather than managing receivables in-house, companies can outsource them. Two options: factoring and invoice discounting.\n\nFactoring. A factoring company takes on your sales ledger. It advances a percentage of invoice value immediately (typically 80–85%), then pays the remainder — less its fees — when the customer settles. Full-service factors also assess customer credit and chase overdue accounts. Non-recourse factoring means the factor absorbs credit risk. Recourse factoring means the risk stays with you.\n\nWorked Example — Mutengo Plc. Mutengo Plc imports commodities sold to reliable customers. Monthly invoices: K300,000. Average credit period: 2.5 months. Terms: a service fee of 2.5% of total invoices, an advance of 85% of invoiced amounts at 13% p.a. interest, and admin cost savings of K95,000 per year avoided.\n\nAnnual sales are K300,000 × 12 = K3,600,000. Factoring fee: 2.5% × K3,600,000 = K90,000. Interest: (2.5/12) × K3,600,000 × 85% × 13% = K82,875. Total factoring cost: K172,875. Less admin cost savings of K95,000, giving a net cost of factoring of K77,875. The alternative — a bank overdraft on K637,500 at 12.5% — costs K79,688. Factoring saves roughly K1,800.\n\nFactoring saves Mutengo about K1,800 per year versus the overdraft — and eliminates the burden of running the sales ledger. For a company that doesn''t want credit management as a core function, the numbers make sense.\n\nInvoice Discounting provides the same finance without handing over your sales ledger. Customers don''t know a third party is involved. It''s cheaper than factoring and keeps the customer relationship entirely in your hands.\n\nComparing the two: on the sales ledger, the factor manages it under factoring while the company manages it under invoice discounting. On customer awareness, customers know under factoring but don''t know under invoice discounting. On cost, factoring is higher and invoice discounting is lower. On best use, factoring suits full outsourcing while invoice discounting suits finance only. On credit risk under non-recourse arrangements, the factor absorbs it under factoring while the company retains it under invoice discounting."}], "keyTerms": [{"term": "Working capital", "definition": "Current assets minus current liabilities — the short-term funding available to run operations"}, {"term": "Cash conversion cycle", "definition": "Days inventory + days receivables - days payables: time from cash outflow to cash inflow"}, {"term": "Days inventory", "definition": "(Inventory ÷ COGS) × 365 — average days inventory is held before being sold"}, {"term": "Days receivables", "definition": "(Receivables ÷ Revenue) × 365 — average days to collect payment from customers"}, {"term": "Days payables", "definition": "(Payables ÷ COGS) × 365 — average days taken to pay suppliers"}, {"term": "Aggressive WC policy", "definition": "Minimal safety stocks and/or short-term financing — higher return, higher risk"}, {"term": "Conservative WC policy", "definition": "Large safety stocks and long-term financing — lower return, lower risk"}, {"term": "Factoring", "definition": "Outsourcing the sales ledger to a finance company that advances cash against invoices"}, {"term": "Invoice discounting", "definition": "Finance advanced against invoices; company retains the sales ledger"}, {"term": "Non-recourse factoring", "definition": "The factor absorbs credit risk — if the customer doesn''t pay, the factor covers it"}, {"term": "Trade discount", "definition": "Reduction offered for early payment, e.g. 2/10 net 30"}], "discussionQuestions": ["If Zanaco ran this same calculation next year and the CCC jumped from 81 days to 120 days, what''s the most likely cause, and which number would you look at first to diagnose it?", "Under what circumstances would you recommend factoring over invoice discounting even if factoring costs more? Think about what else the company gains beyond the finance itself."], "learningOutcomes": ["Define working capital and explain why a profitable business can still fail without adequate liquidity", "Distinguish between aggressive, conservative, and moderate working capital policies for both investment and financing decisions", "Calculate the cash conversion cycle and identify which components to target to shorten it", "Assess whether a buyer should take a trade discount using the annual cost formula", "Explain how factoring works and calculate the net cost of a factoring arrangement", "Compare factoring and invoice discounting and explain when each is more appropriate"]}'::jsonb
where slug = 'working-capital'
  and lesson_id = (select id from lessons where slug = 'working-capital' and course_id = (select id from courses where slug = 'treasury-management'));

update steps set content = '{"sections": [{"eyebrow": "FOUNDATIONS", "heading": "What is Inventory?", "body": "Inventory is stock of raw materials, work in progress, finished goods, and supplies. These materials tie up large amounts of firm resources — cash that could otherwise be used for other investments. The treasury''s goal is to hold the optimum level of inventory that maximises the benefits of holding stock less the costs of doing so.\n\nHold more finished goods and you gain flexibility — you can fill customer orders without waiting for production — but you pay storage, capital, and obsolescence costs. Hold too little and you lose sales when you can''t meet demand. Finding the right balance is a constant challenge.\n\nThere are five types of inventory. Raw materials are the basic inputs to production, separating the timing of supplier deliveries from production scheduling. Work in progress consists of items actively in the manufacturing process. Finished goods are completed items ready for sale, allowing you to fill orders without waiting for production. Scrap and obsolete items are inventory that becomes obsolete with product changes — some can be reused, such as steel or aluminium, or sold to recyclers. Stores and supplies are indirect purchases that support production, such as lubricating oils, maintenance materials, and consumables."}, {"eyebrow": "FINANCING", "heading": "Inventory Financing Alternatives", "body": "Inventory must be financed. There are five main methods available, each with different costs and risk profiles.\n\nTrade credit (accounts payable) is the least expensive form of inventory financing. As you buy goods, the supplier allows you time to pay — typically 30–60 days. This credit is spontaneous: it rises and falls with your inventory levels. You don''t apply for it; it happens automatically.\n\nSupply chain financing is when the seller arranges finance for the buyer based on purchase orders with large buyers. The buyer chooses it (not the supplier), and the seller gets a lower interest rate because the large buyer guarantees the order. The buyer avoids recording the debt on its balance sheet.\n\nCollateralised loans use inventory as collateral for a bank loan. The bank lends a predetermined percentage of inventory value — typically 50–80%. The lien is perfected against the inventory.\n\nAsset-based loans have the lender advance money based on inventory value, not the company''s financial strength. If the company defaults, the lender takes physical possession of the inventory — either through a public warehouse or a field warehouse managed by the lender''s representative.\n\nFloor planning is common for high-value durables like cars, trucks, and heavy equipment. The lender grants loans against individual items by serial number. When the item is sold, the loan is repaid."}, {"eyebrow": "OPERATIONS", "heading": "Just-In-Time (JIT) Purchasing", "body": "JIT minimises inventory by reducing costs and uncertainties. The principle is simple: materials are received just in time to use, not weeks before.\n\nJIT purchasing objectives include reduction of raw material stock, frequent deliveries of smaller orders from fewer suppliers, long-term supplier contracts to enable schedule predictability, and quality assurance where the supplier is responsible for inspection, not the buyer.\n\nJIT production aims for low-cost, high-quality, on-time production to order. This is achieved by minimising idle stock between processes.\n\nThe benefits of JIT include reduced inventory levels that lower storage and capital costs, savings in storage space and handling, increased customer satisfaction through elimination of waste leading to better quality, early identification of weaknesses such as bottlenecks, supplier reliability, and documentation gaps, and flexibility to supply small batches to meet demand variation."}, {"eyebrow": "OPTIMIZATION", "heading": "Economic Order Quantity (EOQ)", "body": "EOQ is the quantity to order each time that minimises total inventory cost. Total cost is the sum of ordering costs and holding costs. Ordering costs fall as order size rises (fewer orders), but holding costs rise (more to store). EOQ is the point where the two balance.\n\nThe formula is: EOQ = √(2ac ÷ h), where a = annual demand in units, c = cost of ordering per order (fixed, regardless of quantity), and h = holding cost per unit per annum.\n\nWorked example — XYZ Ltd: XYZ Ltd requires 1,000 units of material X per month. Cost per order is K30 (regardless of order size). Holding cost is K2.88 per unit per annum.\n\nStep 1: Annual demand = 1,000 × 12 = 12,000 units. Step 2: EOQ = √(2 × 12,000 × 30 ÷ 2.88) = √(720,000 ÷ 2.88) = √250,000 = 500 units. Step 3: Number of orders per year = 12,000 ÷ 500 = 24 orders; time between orders = 365 ÷ 24 = approximately 15.2 days.\n\nXYZ should order 500 units each time they place an order. This means placing 24 orders per year, approximately once every 15 days. This quantity minimises the combined cost of placing orders and holding inventory.", "callout": {"label": "Exam Tip", "body": "Exam tip: EOQ minimises the sum of ordering costs and holding costs. As order size increases, holding costs rise but ordering frequency (and cost) falls. EOQ is the crossover point. You may be asked to calculate EOQ, number of orders per year, or time between orders."}}, {"eyebrow": "PAYABLES", "heading": "Creditor Management", "body": "Trade credit is normally viewed as a free source of finance. The standard treasury policy is to pay suppliers as late as possible — while honouring your obligations and maintaining good relationships. This maximises your use of the creditor as a source of working capital finance.\n\nBut there''s a risk: if you delay payment too long, cash-strapped suppliers may struggle and ultimately fail. That threatens your supply chain and your ability to source materials. Creditor management mirrors debtor management. The same metrics apply in reverse.\n\nDays Payables = (Payables ÷ Cost of Goods Sold) × 365. This measures the average number of days you take to pay suppliers.\n\nExtending payable days reduces the cash conversion cycle and reduces working capital requirements. But it must be balanced against supplier relationships and supply chain risk. Paying too late can damage relationships and threaten supply security."}], "keyTerms": [{"term": "Inventory", "definition": "Stock of raw materials, work in progress, finished goods, and supplies"}, {"term": "Raw materials", "definition": "Basic inputs to production; separates supplier timing from production scheduling"}, {"term": "Work in progress (WIP)", "definition": "Items actively in the manufacturing process"}, {"term": "Finished goods", "definition": "Completed items ready for sale; allows fulfilling orders without waiting for production"}, {"term": "Trade credit", "definition": "Spontaneous credit from suppliers; rises and falls with inventory levels"}, {"term": "Supply chain financing", "definition": "Seller-arranged finance for buyers based on purchase orders with large buyers"}, {"term": "Collateralised loan", "definition": "Inventory as collateral for a bank loan at a predetermined percentage of value"}, {"term": "Asset-based lending", "definition": "Lending based on inventory value, not financial strength; lender takes possession on default"}, {"term": "Floor planning", "definition": "Loans against high-value durables by serial number; repaid when item is sold"}, {"term": "Just-in-time (JIT)", "definition": "Inventory system where materials arrive just in time to use, minimising stock levels"}, {"term": "Economic Order Quantity (EOQ)", "definition": "Order quantity that minimises total inventory cost (ordering + holding)"}, {"term": "Ordering costs", "definition": "Fixed costs incurred each time an order is placed, regardless of quantity"}, {"term": "Holding costs", "definition": "Costs of storing inventory: capital, storage, obsolescence, insurance"}, {"term": "Days payables", "definition": "(Payables ÷ COGS) × 365 — average days to pay suppliers"}, {"term": "Creditor management", "definition": "Managing supplier relationships and payment timing to optimise working capital"}], "discussionQuestions": ["JIT was designed for Toyota''s manufacturing environment. Think about a Zambian manufacturer you know of — what are the two biggest practical barriers to implementing JIT successfully in that context, and how would you address them?", "A company''s finance director proposes stretching supplier payment terms from 30 days to 90 days across all suppliers to improve cash flow. The procurement director objects. Who do you think has the stronger argument, and what would you recommend instead?"], "learningOutcomes": ["Define inventory and identify the five main types and their role in operations", "Describe the five methods of inventory financing and explain when each is appropriate", "Explain the objectives of JIT purchasing and identify practical barriers in a Zambian manufacturing context", "Calculate the Economic Order Quantity and determine the optimal order frequency", "Explain days payables and how creditor management affects the cash conversion cycle", "Balance the benefits of extending payment terms against supply chain relationship risk"]}'::jsonb
where slug = 'inventory-management'
  and lesson_id = (select id from lessons where slug = 'working-capital' and course_id = (select id from courses where slug = 'treasury-management'));

update steps set content = '{"sections": [{"eyebrow": "FOUNDATIONS", "heading": "Why Cash Management Matters", "body": "Cash holds the central position in short-term financing decisions. Holding cash has an opportunity cost — money in the vault earns no interest when it could be generating returns elsewhere. Treasury must balance the liquidity of cash against the profitability forgone by holding it.\n\nThe principle is straightforward: cash should be held only until the marginal value of liquidity equals the value of interest lost. Beyond that point, excess cash is simply idle capital.\n\nCash management, at its heart, is two things: optimising the amount of cash available to meet obligations, and maximising the interest earned on surplus funds not required immediately. Both require careful planning and execution.\n\nThe time value of money plays a key role here. Banks pay higher interest on longer-notice accounts (the longer you tie up the money, the better the rate), and they charge higher rates on overdrafts compared to term loans (the more flexible the facility, the more expensive it is). Treasury''s job is to switch money between accounts to minimise aggregate costs, accounting for the transaction costs of moving funds and the interest rate differentials between accounts."}, {"eyebrow": "BAUMOL MODEL", "heading": "Baumol Model of Cash Management", "body": "The Baumol model is a straightforward approach that helps companies find the desirable cash balance when cash needs are known with certainty. It captures the central trade-off in cash management: the liquidity benefit of holding money against the interest forgone on cash balances that are sitting idle.\n\nKey Variables: Nominal interest rate (i) — the opportunity cost of holding cash. Level of real income (desired transactions) — the annual volume of cash needs. Fixed cost of transferring assets (F) — the cost to move money in or out of the account.\n\nAssumptions: Cash needs are known with certainty; disbursements occur uniformly throughout the period. Opportunity cost is known and constant over the period. Transaction costs are known and constant (the cost to move money doesn''t change with the amount moved).\n\nThe Formula: C = √(2AF / O), where C = optimum cash balance, A = annual cash disbursements, F = fixed cost per transaction, O = opportunity cost (interest rate).\n\nWorked Example — ABC Ltd: ABC Ltd disburses K300,000 per year. The bank pays 10% per annum on money held. Each withdrawal from the investment account costs K20 in fees.\n\nC = √(2 × K20 × K300,000 / 0.10) = √(K120,000,000) = K11,000. Number of transactions = K300,000 ÷ K11,000 = 27 per year. Average balance held = K11,000 ÷ 2 = K5,500. Annual transaction cost = 27 × K20 = K540. Annual opportunity cost = K5,500 × 10% = K550. Total annual cost = K1,090.\n\nThe Baumol model tells ABC Ltd that the optimal balance is K11,000. At that level, the cost of making 27 transactions (K540) roughly equals the interest forgone on the average K5,500 held (K550). Any balance higher or lower would increase total costs."}, {"eyebrow": "MILLER-ORR MODEL", "heading": "Miller-Orr Model of Cash Management", "body": "The Miller-Orr model, developed by M.H. Miller and Daniel Orr, relaxes the Baumol assumption that cash flows are certain. It''s a stochastic model designed for the real world, where cash inflows and outflows are unpredictable.\n\nInstead of calculating a single optimum balance, Miller-Orr establishes control limits: an upper control limit (where you buy marketable securities), a lower control limit (where you sell marketable securities to raise cash), and a return point (where you return the balance after a transaction).\n\nThe Formula: Z = 3∛(3 × transaction cost × variance / 4 × interest rate). Upper control limit = Lower limit + Z. Return point = Lower limit + (Z / 3).\n\nWorked Example — Miller-Orr Calculation: A company sets a lower cash limit of K1,000. The daily interest rate is 0.025% (0.0000025 decimal). The standard deviation of daily cash flows is K500; variance is K250,000. The cost to buy or sell securities is K20.\n\nZ = 3∛[(3 ÷ 4) × K20 × K250,000 / 0.000025] = 3∛[0.75 × K5,000,000 / 0.000025] = 3∛[K150,000,000,000] = 3 × K5,313.63 = K7,400 (rounded). Upper control limit = K1,000 + K7,400 = K8,400. Return point = K1,000 + (K7,400 ÷ 3) = K1,000 + K2,467 = K3,467.\n\nThe model tells management: if cash falls to K1,000, sell securities to raise cash. If cash rises to K8,400, buy securities. After each transaction, target a return point of K3,467.", "callout": {"label": "Exam Tip", "body": "Baumol assumes certainty; Miller-Orr handles uncertainty. Know which to use. You may be asked to calculate the spread (Z), upper control limit, or return point. Miller-Orr is almost always the right choice for real-world exams because cash flows are rarely certain."}}, {"eyebrow": "FORECASTING", "heading": "Cash Flow Forecasting", "body": "Cash forecasting assists treasury in planning cash management activities. It helps schedule transfers between accounts, fund disbursements, make short-term investment or borrowing decisions, and establish target cash balances.\n\nThree Steps to Forecasting: Estimate future inflows and outflows. Generate a pro forma cash position for the forecast period. Identify how to cover deficits (through borrowing or asset sales) or invest surpluses (in short-term instruments).\n\nPurpose of Cash Forecasting: Managing liquidity — forecast the net cash position to identify excesses or shortages for investment or borrowing decisions. Controlling financial activities — identify unanticipated inventory changes, delays in accounts receivable collection, mistimed payments, or fraud. Meeting strategic objectives — project future funding requirements to support growth and strategic expansion plans. Budgeting capital — help evaluate proposed capital expenditures and their impact on cash available for operations. Managing costs — minimise excess bank balances (which earn low interest), reduce short-term borrowing costs, and increase investment income. Managing currency exposure — assess the degree of FX exposure and plan hedging if needed. Regulatory compliance — ensure compliance with regulatory requirements (minimum capital ratios, imprest tax accounts, etc.).\n\nReceipts and Disbursements Method: The receipts and disbursements forecast projects cash in and cash out, then nets them to show the forecast cash position. Receipts schedule: projection of collections from customers, plus other inflows (interest income, dividends, asset sales). Disbursement schedule: forecasting cash out for purchases, payroll, taxes, interest, dividends, rent, debt repayment, capital expenditure. Combined forecast: netting receipts against disbursements and comparing to the minimum cash balance required.\n\nDistribution Forecasts: Distribution forecasts estimate the daily impact of a single event on cash flows over a period, using historical patterns to project how the event unfolds. A large customer payment, for example, may be collected over several days. Historical data shows the pattern of collection, which is then applied to future payments.\n\nStatistical Methods — three common approaches:\n\nSimple Moving Average: a rolling average of past values. The forecast for the next period is the average of the previous n periods. Forecast (day 6) = (Day 1 + Day 2 + Day 3 + Day 4 + Day 5) ÷ 5. Example: past 5 days were K110,000, K120,000, K115,000, K122,000, K126,000. Forecast = (K110,000 + K120,000 + K115,000 + K122,000 + K126,000) ÷ 5 = K118,600. Actual day 6 = K124,000. Forecast error = K124,000 - K118,600 = K5,400.\n\nExponential Smoothing: a weighted average that gives more weight to recent observations and less weight to older ones. The smoothing constant α (alpha) controls how much weight recent data receives (0 < α < 1). Forecast (t+1) = α × Actual (t) + (1 - α) × Forecast (t). Example with α = 0.40: Forecast (day 7) = 0.40 × K124,000 + 0.60 × K118,600 = K49,600 + K71,160 = K120,760.\n\nCorrelation and Regression: identifies association between a cash flow and another variable (e.g., sales volume, production units, customer orders). The regression equation Y = a + bX quantifies the relationship and allows forecasting based on the independent variable."}, {"eyebrow": "SURPLUSES", "heading": "Managing Cash Surpluses & Short-Term Investment", "body": "Cash surpluses arise for many reasons — seasonal variations, uneven project timing, unexpected recoveries from receivables. When cash sits idle, it earns nothing unless it''s invested. The key is finding the right home for it.\n\nWhen deciding where to invest surplus cash, ask four questions: How long can the cash be tied up? How much is available? What return can be earned? What''s the risk of early withdrawal?\n\nShort-Term Investment Vehicles: Treasury bills — government short-term debt, issued at a discount to par; good liquidity, fixed maturity, low risk. Call deposits — current accounts paying interest, notice period required; combines liquidity with interest, can access with notice. Term deposits — fixed amount for a fixed period (30, 60, 90, 120 days), tiered rates; higher rates for longer commitment, no early access. Certificates of deposit — fixed-rate instruments issued by commercial banks; tradeable on the discount market, reasonable liquidity. Money market accounts — variable-rate investment in money markets; flexible, market-linked returns, instant access.\n\nTreasury Bill Yield Calculation: Treasury bills are issued at a discount to their par value. The yield depends on the purchase price and days to maturity. Yield = (100 - Purchase Price) ÷ Purchase Price × 100. Annualised Return = Yield × 365 ÷ Days to Maturity. Example: a 91-day T-bill purchased at K99. Yield = (100 - 99) ÷ 99 × 100 = 1.01%. Annualised yield = 1.01% × 365 ÷ 91 = 4.05%.\n\nA K99 purchase of a 91-day bill yields 4.05% annualised — better than a call deposit at 2%, but the money is tied up for three months."}, {"eyebrow": "BORROWING", "heading": "Bank Overdrafts", "body": "A bank overdraft is a short-term advance on the current account, repayable within 12 months, up to an agreed limit. Interest is charged on the daily balance outstanding (not on the full facility).\n\nOverdrafts are used by companies for working capital gaps and by individuals for salary timing or consumer purchases. They''re the default short-term borrowing tool for many businesses.\n\nAdvantages: Flexibility — draw funds only when needed; repay when you have cash, with no drawn-down fees. Minimal documentation — easier and faster to arrange than a term loan, with less legal paperwork. Interest efficiency — interest is paid on the overdrawn amount, not on the full facility; secured overdrafts usually have lower rates.\n\nDisadvantages: Repayable on demand — the bank can call the facility with notice. Collateral required — the bank will demand security (personal guarantee, asset charge, or cash deposit). Interest rate risk — the rate is variable, floating with base rate changes. Cost varies by perceived risk — healthier businesses get better rates."}, {"eyebrow": "CONCENTRATION", "heading": "Cash Concentration", "body": "Large, multi-site organisations maintain different bank accounts across regions or business units. Money scattered across many accounts makes it hard to fund centralised payments, invest surpluses efficiently, or track the true cash position. The solution is cash concentration — pooling cash from multiple accounts.\n\nPhysical Sweeping moves cash between accounts, in three approaches.\n\nZero Balance Account (ZBA): the bank automatically sweeps cash from subsidiary accounts into the concentration account at the end of each day. Each subsidiary ZBA is reduced to zero on the sweep. Funds are transferred back to the subsidiary when it has a debit balance.\n\nConstant Balancing: the bank maintains a pre-determined minimum balance in each subsidiary account. Any amount above the minimum is swept to the concentration account. If the subsidiary balance falls below the minimum, funds are transferred back.\n\nTrigger Balances: sweeping occurs only when a subsidiary account balance exceeds a trigger level (e.g., K100,000). This reduces the frequency of sweeps (perhaps weekly or monthly) but requires a higher trigger balance.\n\nNotional Pooling calculates interest on the combined credit and debit balances of all subsidiary accounts without physically transferring funds. Each subsidiary retains daily cash management privileges (can move its own money), but interest is earned on the net balance of the pool. The advantage: interest earnings are higher than separate accounts, and it avoids intercompany loans and bank transfer fees. The disadvantage: notional pooling is not permitted in some countries (parts of Africa, Asia, and Latin America). Global pooling can offset multicurrency balances without executing foreign exchange transactions.\n\nComparison — Physical Sweeping (ZBA) vs Notional Pooling: Funds physically moved — yes for physical sweeping, no for notional pooling. Intercompany loans — may arise under physical sweeping, not required under notional pooling. Bank transfer fees — charged under physical sweeping, not under notional pooling. Permitted everywhere — physical sweeping is generally permitted everywhere, while notional pooling is restricted in some countries. Subsidiary autonomy — reduced under physical sweeping (account zeroed daily), maintained under notional pooling."}], "keyTerms": [{"term": "Cash management", "definition": "The practice of optimising the cash available to meet obligations while maximising returns on surplus funds"}, {"term": "Opportunity cost (cash)", "definition": "The interest or return forgone by holding non-interest-bearing cash"}, {"term": "Baumol model", "definition": "A deterministic model that calculates the optimum cash balance when cash flows are certain"}, {"term": "Miller-Orr model", "definition": "A stochastic model that establishes control limits and a return point for cash management under uncertainty"}, {"term": "Control limits (upper/lower)", "definition": "In Miller-Orr, the thresholds at which the company buys/sells securities"}, {"term": "Return point", "definition": "In Miller-Orr, the balance to which cash is returned after a transaction"}, {"term": "Cash flow forecasting", "definition": "Predicting future cash inflows and outflows to plan working capital management"}, {"term": "Receipts and disbursements forecast", "definition": "A detailed schedule of projected cash in and cash out"}, {"term": "Moving average", "definition": "A forecast based on the average of past values"}, {"term": "Exponential smoothing", "definition": "A forecast that weights recent observations more heavily than older ones"}, {"term": "Treasury bill", "definition": "Short-term government debt issued at a discount"}, {"term": "Call deposit", "definition": "An interest-bearing current account requiring notice before withdrawal"}, {"term": "Term deposit", "definition": "An interest-bearing deposit locked in for a fixed period"}, {"term": "Certificate of deposit", "definition": "A fixed-rate bank instrument, typically tradeable"}, {"term": "Bank overdraft", "definition": "A short-term advance on the current account, repayable on demand"}, {"term": "Cash concentration", "definition": "Pooling cash from multiple accounts into a single account"}, {"term": "Zero balance account (ZBA)", "definition": "A subsidiary account that is swept daily to zero, with funds transferred to a concentration account"}, {"term": "Notional pooling", "definition": "Interest calculation on combined balances without physically moving funds"}], "discussionQuestions": ["A company''s cash flows are highly unpredictable due to seasonal demand. Which model — Baumol or Miller-Orr — is more appropriate, and what data would you need to apply it?", "ABC Ltd''s treasurer is considering raising the lower cash limit in the Miller-Orr model. What effect does this have on the upper limit and return point?"], "learningOutcomes": ["Explain the concept of cash management and the trade-off between liquidity and profitability", "Apply the Baumol model to calculate the optimum cash balance under certainty", "Apply the Miller-Orr model to determine the spread, upper limit and return point under uncertainty", "Distinguish between Baumol and Miller-Orr and identify which model is appropriate in a given context", "Identify the purposes of cash flow forecasting and explain the main forecasting methods", "Calculate treasury bill yields and evaluate short-term investment vehicles for surplus cash", "Explain the advantages and disadvantages of bank overdrafts as a source of short-term finance", "Distinguish between physical sweeping and notional pooling as cash concentration strategies"]}'::jsonb
where slug = 'cash-management'
  and lesson_id = (select id from lessons where slug = 'working-capital' and course_id = (select id from courses where slug = 'treasury-management'));

update steps set content = '{"sections": [{"eyebrow": "FOUNDATIONS", "heading": "What Is Interest Rate Risk?", "body": "Interest rate risk is the potential loss in a firm''s profitability and market value arising from unexpected changes in interest rate levels. Every company with floating-rate debt, variable-rate borrowings, or fixed-income investments is exposed to this risk. When you borrow at a floating rate pegged to LIBOR or the Bank of Zambia policy rate, a rise in that reference rate directly increases your borrowing cost. Equally, if you hold fixed-rate bonds and interest rates rise, the market value of those bonds falls.\n\nTypes of Interest Rate Risk: Repricing risk arises when assets and liabilities have different repricing dates. For example, a 5-year loan funding a 3-year investment means a repricing gap after 3 years. Basis risk occurs when the reference rates on a firm''s assets and liabilities move differently. A loan on LIBOR+2% funding an asset on prime rate creates basis risk. Yield curve risk is caused by changes in the shape of the yield curve (the term structure of rates), which affect firms differently depending on whether they borrow long or short term. Options risk (embedded options) arises from bonds with embedded call or put options, which create asymmetric risk — borrowers can refinance if rates fall; lenders cannot fully capture upside if rates rise."}, {"eyebrow": "MEASUREMENT", "heading": "Measuring Interest Rate Exposure", "body": "Treasury cannot manage what it cannot measure. Three key tools quantify interest rate sensitivity: gap analysis (repricing schedule), duration, and basis point value.\n\n1. Gap Analysis (Repricing Schedule): Gap analysis groups assets and liabilities by their repricing dates. The interest rate gap in any time bucket is the difference between rate-sensitive assets (RSA) and rate-sensitive liabilities (RSL) maturing or repricing in that period. The formula is: Gap = RSA — RSL. A positive gap means more assets reprice up than liabilities — if rates rise, net interest income rises. A negative gap means more liabilities reprice — if rates rise, net interest income falls. Gap analysis helps treasury decide whether to hedge.\n\n2. Duration: Duration measures the weighted-average time to receive a bond''s cash flows, expressed in years. It is the primary measure of interest rate sensitivity for fixed-income securities. A bond with 5-year duration will lose approximately 5% in value if yields rise by 1% (100 basis points). The formula is: Price change (%) is approximately equal to −Duration × Yield change (%).\n\n3. Basis Point Value (BPV): This is the dollar impact of a 1 basis point (0.01%) move in interest rates. For a ZMW 1 million notional principal, a 1 bp move in a 6-month rate implies a change in interest cost of ZMW 1m × 0.0001 × 0.5 = ZMW 50 per annum."}, {"eyebrow": "INSTRUMENTS", "heading": "Hedging with Forward Rate Agreements (FRAs)", "body": "A Forward Rate Agreement (FRA) is an over-the-counter contract in which two parties lock in an interest rate today for a loan or deposit to be made at a specified future date. Unlike bonds, FRAs require no principal exchange — only the interest rate difference is settled in cash.\n\nHow FRAs Work: Suppose it is March and a company has a ZMW 1 million loan resetting in 6 months. The treasurer fears rates will rise. Current 6-month rates are 7%, but an FRA dealer quotes 7.5% for a 6-month loan starting in 6 months. The company buys the FRA at 7.5%.", "callout": {"label": "Fact", "body": "Scenario 1 (Rates Rise to 8%): The company pays the market rate of 8% on its loan but receives (8.0% − 7.5%) × ZMW 1m × 0.5 = ZMW 2,500 from the FRA counterparty. Net cost: 8.0% − 0.5% = 7.5%. The FRA locked in the 7.5% rate.\n\nScenario 2 (Rates Fall to 6%): The company pays the market rate of 6% on its loan but pays (7.5% − 6.0%) × ZMW 1m × 0.5 = ZMW 7,500 to the FRA counterparty. Net cost: 6.0% + 1.5% = 7.5%. The FRA still locks in 7.5%, sacrificing the benefit of falling rates."}}, {"eyebrow": "SWAPS", "heading": "Interest Rate Swaps (IRS)", "body": "An Interest Rate Swap (IRS) is an agreement between two parties to exchange periodic interest payments on a notional principal amount. One party pays fixed; the other pays floating. The notional principal is never exchanged — only the interest difference flows between parties. Swaps are longer-term than FRAs (typically 2–10 years) and allow firms to transform their debt structure without refinancing.\n\nWhy Companies Use Swaps: firms transform debt structure — a company borrowing at floating can swap into fixed (or vice versa). Firms can also exploit comparative advantage — if one party has a lower fixed-rate cost and another has a lower floating rate, a swap can benefit both (as in the Zambia Sugar / Lafarge example). Swaps also offer a longer horizon, typically covering 2–10 years, longer than FRAs.\n\nWorked Example: The Zambia Sugar / Lafarge Swap. Zambia Sugar Plc has a AAA credit rating and can borrow at 10% fixed or LIBOR+0.3% floating. Lafarge Cement Plc has a BBB rating and can borrow at 11% fixed or LIBOR+0.5% floating. Zambia Sugar wants floating cost; Lafarge wants fixed cost.\n\nMarket rate comparison: Zambia Sugar can borrow at 10% fixed or LIBOR+0.3% floating. Lafarge can borrow at 11% fixed or LIBOR+0.5% floating. This gives Zambia Sugar an absolute advantage of 1% and a comparative advantage of 0.2%.\n\nSwap structure: Zambia Sugar borrows at 10% fixed; Lafarge borrows at LIBOR+0.5% floating. They agree that Zambia Sugar pays LIBOR to Lafarge, and Lafarge pays 10.1% to Zambia Sugar.\n\nOutcome for each party: Zambia Sugar pays 10% to the market, receives 10.1% from Lafarge, and pays LIBOR to Lafarge — a net cost of LIBOR − 0.1%, saving 0.4% versus borrowing at LIBOR+0.3%. Lafarge pays LIBOR+0.5% to the market, receives LIBOR from Zambia Sugar, and pays 10.1% to Zambia Sugar — a net cost of 10.6%, saving 0.4% versus borrowing at 11%.", "callout": {"label": "Note", "body": "Zambia Sugar: Borrows at 10%, receives 10.1% from Lafarge, pays LIBOR to Lafarge. Net cost = LIBOR − 0.1%, a saving of 0.4% versus borrowing at LIBOR+0.3%.\n\nLafarge: Borrows at LIBOR+0.5%, receives LIBOR from Zambia Sugar, pays 10.1% to Zambia Sugar. Net cost = 10.6%, a saving of 0.4% versus borrowing at 11%."}}, {"eyebrow": "FUTURES", "heading": "Interest Rate Futures", "body": "Interest rate futures are standardised, exchange-traded contracts that lock in a borrowing or lending rate for a future date. Unlike over-the-counter FRAs, futures are liquid and can be closed out (sold or bought back) at any time. However, they require margin payments and come in fixed contract sizes.\n\nPricing and Hedging: Interest rate futures prices are quoted as 100 minus the implied interest rate. If a 3-month Euribor futures contract is quoted at 97, the implied rate is 3% (100 − 97). If the rate is expected to rise to 4%, the price falls to 96. A borrower who sells (shorts) the contract gains when rates rise (contract price falls); a lender who buys (goes long) gains when rates fall.\n\nWorked Example: Hedging with Futures. In June, a company has a variable-rate loan of ZMW 1 million resetting in 3 months at a new rate. Current 3-month rates are 5%; the company fears a rise to 6%. A ZMW 1 million futures contract is quoted at 95 (implying 5%).", "callout": {"label": "Note", "body": "Hedge action: The company sells 1 futures contract at 95. If rates rise to 6% in September: The company pays an extra 1% on its loan = ZMW 2,500. But the futures contract now trades at 94 (100 − 6). The company buys it back at 94, gaining 1% on the contract, or ZMW 2,500 per quarter. The gain offsets the higher borrowing cost. Effective hedge cost: The margin requirement (typically 1–2% of notional) and daily mark-to-market volatility. But the rate is locked in."}}, {"eyebrow": "OPTIONS", "heading": "Interest Rate Options (Caps, Floors, Collars)", "body": "Interest rate options give the buyer the right, but not the obligation, to borrow or lend at a fixed rate. Unlike FRAs and swaps (which are binding), options are asymmetric: the buyer pays an upfront premium and then has the choice to exercise or not based on market rates.\n\nThree Main Types: An Interest Rate Cap lets the borrower buy the right to pay a maximum fixed rate. If rates rise above the cap, the seller reimburses the difference. If rates stay below, the borrower walks away (but loses the premium paid). An Interest Rate Floor lets the lender buy the right to receive a minimum fixed rate. If rates fall below the floor, the seller reimburses the difference. An Interest Rate Collar has the borrower buy a cap and simultaneously sell a floor. The premium from selling the floor offsets the cost of the cap, reducing the net cost of the hedge.\n\nWorked Example: Cap vs FRA. XYZ Plc has a ZMW 1 million loan resetting in 3 months. Current rates: 7%. A 3-month FRA is available at 7.5%; a cap at 7.5% strike with 0.3% premium costs ZMW 1,500 (ZMW 1m × 0.003 × 0.5).\n\nIf rates rise to 8%: under the FRA, the rate is locked in at 7.5% — the company receives ZMW 2,500 from the FRA counterparty, for net interest of ZMW 40,500. Under the cap, the company pays the market rate of 8% on the loan, the cap reimburses the difference (8.0% − 7.5%), and with the ZMW 1,500 premium paid, the net cost is ZMW 41,500.\n\nIf rates fall to 6%: under the FRA, the rate is still locked in at 7.5% — the company pays ZMW 7,500 to the FRA counterparty, for net interest of ZMW 40,500. Under the cap, the company pays the market rate of 6%, the cap is not exercised, and with the ZMW 1,500 premium paid, the net cost is ZMW 36,000.\n\nThe FRA locks in 7.5% regardless of market rates. The cap protects against rates rising above 7.5% but lets the borrower benefit if rates fall (minus the premium). This optionality costs ZMW 1,500, but the upside is valuable in uncertain environments."}, {"eyebrow": "CONTEXT", "heading": "Interest Rate Risk in Zambia", "body": "Zambia''s monetary policy is set by the Bank of Zambia Monetary Policy Committee (MPC). In early 2023, the policy rate was in the range of 10–12% per annum, with inflation running at 13–15%. Corporate borrowing rates typically track the policy rate with a spread (prime rate = policy rate + 3–5% for standard lending). A rise in the policy rate cascades quickly through the banking system to floating-rate borrowers and new fixed-rate loans.", "callout": {"label": "Warning", "body": "Why this matters: Zambian companies operating with variable-rate debt face material cost increases when the MPC raises rates to fight inflation. Treasury must actively monitor MPC statements and forward guidance to anticipate rate changes, then decide whether to hedge (lock in fixed rates via swaps or FRAs) or accept the risk."}}], "keyTerms": [{"term": "Interest rate risk", "definition": "Potential loss in firm value or profitability from unexpected changes in interest rates"}, {"term": "Repricing risk", "definition": "Mismatch in repricing dates of assets vs liabilities; gap is positive (asset-heavy) or negative (liability-heavy)"}, {"term": "Basis risk", "definition": "Risk that reference rates on assets and liabilities move differently, creating unhedged exposure"}, {"term": "Yield curve risk", "definition": "Changes in the term structure of rates affecting firms differently based on debt maturity"}, {"term": "Embedded options risk", "definition": "Asymmetric risk from bonds with call/put options; affects borrowers and lenders differently"}, {"term": "Gap analysis", "definition": "Scheduling of rate-sensitive assets (RSA) and liabilities (RSL) by repricing date to measure exposure"}, {"term": "Duration", "definition": "Weighted-average time to cash flows; measure of bond interest rate sensitivity"}, {"term": "Basis point value (BPV)", "definition": "Dollar impact of a 1 bp (0.01%) change in interest rates on a given notional principal"}, {"term": "Forward Rate Agreement (FRA)", "definition": "OTC contract locking in an interest rate for a future loan/deposit; settlement in cash only"}, {"term": "Interest Rate Swap (IRS)", "definition": "Exchange of fixed and floating interest payments on a notional principal; transforms debt structure"}, {"term": "Notional principal", "definition": "The amount on which interest payments are calculated in a swap or FRA; not physically exchanged"}, {"term": "Basis spread", "definition": "Difference between fixed-rate cost and floating-rate cost; opportunity for swap arbitrage"}, {"term": "Interest rate futures", "definition": "Exchange-traded, standardised contracts locking in future borrowing/lending rates"}, {"term": "Hedge ratio", "definition": "The number of contracts (or notional size) required to offset exposure in the underlying loan/investment"}, {"term": "Interest rate cap", "definition": "Option giving the buyer the right to pay a maximum fixed rate; seller reimburses if rates exceed cap"}, {"term": "Interest rate floor", "definition": "Option giving the buyer the right to receive a minimum fixed rate; seller reimburses if rates fall below floor"}, {"term": "Collar", "definition": "Combination of long cap + short floor; reduces net premium cost while capping upside"}, {"term": "Prime rate", "definition": "Benchmark lending rate set by central bank or leading commercial banks (in Zambia, set by Bank of Zambia + spread)"}, {"term": "Policy rate", "definition": "Official interest rate set by the central bank''s Monetary Policy Committee; transmission mechanism for monetary policy"}], "discussionQuestions": ["A company borrows ZMW 5 million on a 3-year floating rate pegged to the Bank of Zambia policy rate + 2%. The current policy rate is 11%. If it rises to 13%, what is the company''s incremental annual cost? How would you use an IRS to hedge?", "Explain why a borrower might prefer a 2-year interest rate cap over a 2-year FRA. When would a collar be a better choice than a cap?"], "learningOutcomes": ["Define interest rate risk and explain the four main types (repricing, basis, yield curve, options)", "Conduct a gap analysis to identify positive and negative repricing gaps in a balance sheet", "Calculate duration and basis point value to quantify interest rate sensitivity", "Structure and evaluate a forward rate agreement (FRA) for a specific interest rate scenario", "Design an interest rate swap to transform floating debt into fixed (or vice versa)", "Use interest rate futures to hedge a floating-rate loan; calculate margin requirements and gains/losses", "Compare interest rate options (caps, floors, collars) against FRAs and swaps; explain when options are preferable", "Apply interest rate hedging techniques in a Zambian context with Bank of Zambia policy rate movements"]}'::jsonb
where slug = 'interest-rate-risk'
  and lesson_id = (select id from lessons where slug = 'risk' and course_id = (select id from courses where slug = 'treasury-management'));

update steps set content = '{"sections": [{"eyebrow": "FOUNDATIONS", "heading": "Types of Foreign Exchange Exposure", "body": "Foreign exchange (FX) risk arises whenever a company deals in multiple currencies. Unlike interest rate risk (which is independent of foreign currency), FX risk affects firms with international operations, cross-border receivables/payables, or foreign investments. Three types of FX exposure exist:\n\n1. Transaction Exposure: Arises from committed foreign currency cash flows. For example, an export sale to a US customer with payment due in 90 days is a transaction exposure. If the USD weakens against the ZMW, the Zambian company receives fewer kwacha for each dollar when it converts the payment. Transaction exposure is the most immediate and quantifiable FX risk.\n\n2. Translation Exposure: Arises from the need to consolidate foreign subsidiary financial statements into the parent company''s home currency. When a foreign subsidiary''s assets, liabilities, or earnings are restated in the parent''s currency, exchange rate changes affect reported equity and earnings. Translation exposure is an accounting issue — it doesn''t reflect cash flow changes — but it affects reported financial performance and may trigger loan covenant violations.\n\n3. Economic Exposure: Arises from the long-term impact of exchange rate changes on a company''s competitive position and future cash flows. If the kwacha strengthens, Zambian exporters become less price-competitive internationally, reducing future sales and cash flows. Economic exposure is the hardest to quantify and hedge, but it is the most strategically important."}, {"eyebrow": "MECHANICS", "heading": "Exchange Rate Quotations and Cross Rates", "body": "Most currencies are quoted in two ways. An indirect quote (or ''American terms'') expresses how much foreign currency is needed to buy one unit of the home currency — e.g., USD/ZMW 12.50 means you need 12.50 kwacha per dollar. A direct quote (or ''European terms'') expresses how much home currency buys one unit of foreign currency — e.g., ZMW/USD 0.0800 means one dollar costs 0.08 kwacha (the inverse of the indirect quote).\n\nBid-Ask Spreads: Banks always quote two rates: the bid rate (the rate at which they buy currency from you) and the ask/offer rate (the rate at which they sell to you). For example, a bank might quote USD/ZMW 12.48–12.52, meaning they will buy dollars at 12.48 kwacha/USD and sell dollars at 12.52 kwacha/USD. The bank profits from the spread (12.52 − 12.48 = 0.04 kwacha per dollar).\n\nCross Rates: A cross rate is an exchange rate between two currencies, neither of which is the US dollar. For example, GBP/ZMW is a cross rate. Cross rates are calculated from two pairs that both involve the dollar (or another common base). If GBP/USD is 1.27 and USD/ZMW is 12.50, then GBP/ZMW = 1.27 × 12.50 = 15.875. The cross rate formula is: Cross Rate (GBP/ZMW) = (GBP/USD) × (USD/ZMW)."}, {"eyebrow": "FORWARD", "heading": "Forward Contracts and Forward Rates", "body": "The spot rate is the current exchange rate for immediate delivery (settlement in 1–2 days). A forward rate is the rate agreed today for delivery at a future date (e.g., 3, 6, or 12 months ahead). Forward rates are derived from spot rates and interest rate differentials between the two countries.\n\nForward Rate Calculation: If the home currency (e.g., ZMW) has a higher interest rate than the foreign currency (e.g., USD), the kwacha is at a forward discount — you must pay more kwacha per dollar in the forward market than spot. Conversely, if USD rates are higher, the kwacha is at a forward premium — you pay fewer kwacha per dollar forward. The formula is: Forward Rate = Spot Rate × (1 + i_home) / (1 + i_foreign), where i_home and i_foreign are the annualized interest rates of the home and foreign currency respectively.\n\nWorked Example: USD/ZMW Forward Rate. Current spot rate: USD/ZMW 12.50. Current interest rates: USD 4% per annum, ZMW 12% per annum. Calculate the 6-month forward rate.\n\nForward Rate = 12.50 × [(1 + 0.12/2) / (1 + 0.04/2)] = 12.50 × [1.06 / 1.02] = 12.50 × 1.0392 = 13.00 kwacha/USD. The kwacha is at a forward discount (you pay 13.00 forward vs 12.50 spot) because ZMW rates are higher. This compensates foreign lenders for holding a higher-yielding but potentially depreciating currency.", "callout": {"label": "Note", "body": "Forward Rate = 12.50 × [(1 + 0.12/2) / (1 + 0.04/2)] = 12.50 × [1.06 / 1.02] = 12.50 × 1.0392 = 13.00 kwacha/USD. The kwacha is at a forward discount (you pay 13.00 forward vs 12.50 spot) because ZMW rates are higher. This compensates foreign lenders for holding a higher-yielding but potentially depreciating currency."}}, {"eyebrow": "STRATEGIES", "heading": "Business Practice Hedging Strategies", "body": "Before resorting to financial hedges (forwards, options, futures), treasury should consider operational strategies that reduce FX exposure at the source.\n\n1. Insist on Home Currency Payment: The simplest strategy: require foreign customers to pay in kwacha. This shifts all FX risk to them. Large, dominant firms can enforce this; smaller firms may lose deals to competitors willing to accept foreign currency.\n\n2. Currency Surcharges: Invoice in home currency but add a clause allowing a surcharge if the exchange rate moves significantly. For example, if ZMW weakens by more than 2%, the customer pays a surcharge to compensate for the FX loss.\n\n3. Accelerate Collections / Extend Payables: If you expect a currency to depreciate, collect receivables in that currency as quickly as possible and delay payables as long as possible (minimize exposure). Conversely, if a currency is expected to appreciate, accelerate payables and delay collections. This is a form of FX speculation, so use it carefully.\n\n4. Source from the Same Country: If a company receives cash in USD from US customers, it should source materials and supplies in USD, offsetting the exposure. This is called a natural hedge — FX gains and losses offset. It is more cost-effective than financial hedges in the long term.\n\n5. Netting: Bilateral netting — if Company A owes Company B ZMW 10 million in USD and Company B owes Company A USD 2 million, only the net USD 8 million flows from A to B. Multinational companies use multilateral netting — a centralized clearing house nets payables and receivables across all subsidiaries, reducing gross FX flows."}, {"eyebrow": "FORWARDS", "heading": "Forward Exchange Contracts", "body": "A forward contract commits the buyer to purchase (or the seller to sell) a fixed amount of currency at a predetermined forward rate on a specified future date. Unlike options, forwards are binding on both parties — there is no choice to walk away. This makes forwards cheaper than options but riskier if the market moves in your favour.\n\nWorked Example: Hedging a USD Receivable. A Zambian exporter is due to receive USD 500,000 from a US buyer in 3 months. Spot rate: USD/ZMW 12.50. 3-month forward rate: USD/ZMW 13.00. The exporter fears kwacha appreciation (fewer kwacha per dollar). The exporter enters a forward contract to sell USD 500,000 at 13.00 ZMW/USD in 3 months.\n\nScenario 1 (spot moves to 12.00 ZMW/USD — kwacha appreciates): if not hedged, the exporter receives only 500,000 × 12.00 = ZMW 6,000,000. With the forward hedge, the exporter locks in 500,000 × 13.00 = ZMW 6,500,000. The hedge gains ZMW 500,000.\n\nScenario 2 (spot moves to 14.00 ZMW/USD — kwacha depreciates): if not hedged, the exporter receives 500,000 × 14.00 = ZMW 7,000,000. With the forward hedge, the exporter locks in 500,000 × 13.00 = ZMW 6,500,000. The hedge costs ZMW 500,000 in foregone gains.", "callout": {"label": "Note", "body": "Scenario 1 (Spot moves to 12.00 ZMW/USD — kwacha appreciates): If not hedged, the exporter receives only 500,000 × 12.00 = ZMW 6,000,000. With the forward hedge, the exporter locks in 500,000 × 13.00 = ZMW 6,500,000. The hedge gains ZMW 500,000. Scenario 2 (Spot moves to 14.00 ZMW/USD — kwacha depreciates): If not hedged, the exporter receives 500,000 × 14.00 = ZMW 7,000,000. With the forward hedge, the exporter locks in 500,000 × 13.00 = ZMW 6,500,000. The hedge costs ZMW 500,000 in foregone gains."}}, {"eyebrow": "FUTURES", "heading": "Currency Futures", "body": "Like interest rate futures, currency futures are standardised, exchange-traded contracts for a fixed amount of currency (e.g., USD 62,500) at a future date. They require margin, are marked-to-market daily, and can be closed out before maturity. The main advantage over forwards: liquidity and lower counterparty risk. The disadvantage: less flexibility in contract size and date.\n\nWorked Example: Hedging a Large USD Receivable with Futures. XYZ Ltd, a Zambian manufacturing company, expects to receive USD 2,650,000 from US customers in 3 months (August). Spot rate (June): USD/ZMW 10.11. September USD/ZMW futures are quoted at 9.92. XYZ fears kwacha appreciation (it wants to lock in the highest kwacha per dollar possible).\n\nStandard USD/ZMW futures contract size: USD 62,500. Number of contracts needed: USD 2,650,000 / USD 62,500 = 42 contracts.\n\nHedge action: XYZ sells 42 September USD/ZMW futures at 9.92. If spot moves to 8.25 (kwacha appreciates): spot receipt would be USD 2,650,000 × 8.25 = ZMW 21,862,500. Futures gain: (9.92 − 8.25) × 42 × USD 62,500 = ZMW 4,383,750. Total cash: ZMW 21,862,500 + ZMW 4,383,750 = ZMW 26,246,250. This is much better than the unhedged ZMW 21,862,500.", "callout": {"label": "Note", "body": "Hedge action: XYZ sells 42 September USD/ZMW futures at 9.92. If spot moves to 8.25 (kwacha appreciates): spot receipt would be USD 2,650,000 × 8.25 = ZMW 21,862,500. Futures gain: (9.92 − 8.25) × 42 × USD 62,500 = ZMW 4,383,750. Total cash: ZMW 21,862,500 + ZMW 4,383,750 = ZMW 26,246,250. This is much better than the unhedged ZMW 21,862,500."}}, {"eyebrow": "OPTIONS", "heading": "Currency Options and Strategies", "body": "A currency option gives the buyer the right, but not the obligation, to exchange currencies at a strike price on or before a future date. Call options on foreign currency give the right to buy; put options give the right to sell. Like interest rate options, currency options require an upfront premium but offer flexibility — if the market moves in your favour, you walk away and keep the premium loss; if it moves against you, you exercise and lock in the strike rate.\n\nPuts, Calls, and Real-World Strategies: An importer expecting to pay USD 1 million in 6 months buys a USD put option (the right to sell ZMW or buy USD at a fixed rate). This limits downside if the kwacha weakens but lets the importer benefit if the kwacha strengthens — minus the premium paid. An exporter expecting to receive USD buys a USD call option (the right to buy USD at a fixed rate, which is equivalent to selling ZMW at a fixed kwacha/USD rate).\n\nOptions vs Forwards vs Futures: comparing the three instruments across key features — a forward contract is binding on both parties, fully customizable in amount and date, low cost (no upfront premium), has low liquidity (no secondary market), carries high counterparty risk (bilateral agreement), and is best used when an exact amount and date are needed. Futures are also binding on both parties, but limited to standardised sizes and dates, low cost (margin only), high liquidity (exchange traded), low counterparty risk (exchange guaranteed), and best used for general hedging with frequent adjustment. Options are not binding — the buyer may walk away — limited to standardised sizes and dates, high cost (premium paid upfront), medium liquidity (less liquid than futures), medium counterparty risk (exchange guaranteed), and best used when optionality and upside capture are wanted."}, {"eyebrow": "CONTEXT", "heading": "FX Risk in Zambia", "body": "The Zambian kwacha is a free-floating currency. Since 2015, it has depreciated significantly against the US dollar and other major currencies, driven by inflation, capital outflows, and commodity price shocks. At the time of writing (early 2023), the exchange rate was approximately ZMW 20–25 per USD (though it has recovered to 12–13 in recent quarters). For Zambian companies with USD receivables or borrowings, this volatility is material.\n\nPolicy context: The Bank of Zambia manages FX markets and occasionally intervenes to stabilize the kwacha, though it has stepped back from active intervention in recent years, allowing market forces to prevail. Companies must monitor MPC statements and BoZ FX market updates to anticipate volatility. For firms with large USD receivables, forward contracts and options are essential tools to lock in rates and manage earnings volatility.", "callout": {"label": "Warning", "body": "The Bank of Zambia manages FX markets and occasionally intervenes to stabilize the kwacha, though it has stepped back from active intervention in recent years, allowing market forces to prevail. Companies must monitor MPC statements and BoZ FX market updates to anticipate volatility. For firms with large USD receivables, forward contracts and options are essential tools to lock in rates and manage earnings volatility."}}], "keyTerms": [{"term": "Foreign exchange risk", "definition": "Potential loss from unexpected changes in exchange rates affecting reported earnings or cash flows"}, {"term": "Transaction exposure", "definition": "FX risk from committed foreign currency cash flows (receivables, payables, future contracts)"}, {"term": "Translation exposure", "definition": "FX risk from consolidating foreign subsidiary statements into parent currency; affects reported equity/earnings"}, {"term": "Economic exposure", "definition": "Long-term FX risk from exchange rate impacts on competitive position and future cash flows"}, {"term": "Indirect quote", "definition": "Exchange rate expressing foreign currency units per home currency unit (e.g., USD/ZMW 12.50)"}, {"term": "Direct quote", "definition": "Exchange rate expressing home currency units per foreign currency unit (e.g., ZMW/USD 0.0800)"}, {"term": "Bid-ask spread", "definition": "Difference between bank''s buying rate (bid) and selling rate (ask/offer); the bank''s profit margin"}, {"term": "Cross rate", "definition": "Exchange rate between two currencies, neither of which is the US dollar; calculated from two dollar pairs"}, {"term": "Spot rate", "definition": "Current exchange rate for immediate (1–2 day) delivery"}, {"term": "Forward rate", "definition": "Exchange rate agreed today for delivery at a future date (3, 6, 12 months, etc.)"}, {"term": "Forward discount", "definition": "When the forward rate is higher (in indirect quote terms) than the spot — home currency is at a discount"}, {"term": "Forward premium", "definition": "When the forward rate is lower than the spot — home currency is at a premium"}, {"term": "Forward contract", "definition": "OTC agreement to exchange currencies at a fixed rate on a future date; binding on both parties"}, {"term": "Currency futures", "definition": "Exchange-traded, standardised contracts for currency delivery; highly liquid but less flexible than forwards"}, {"term": "Natural hedge", "definition": "Offsetting FX exposure by sourcing and selling in the same foreign currency"}, {"term": "Bilateral netting", "definition": "Agreement between two parties to exchange net cash flows rather than gross flows"}, {"term": "Multilateral netting", "definition": "Centralized clearing of payables and receivables across multiple subsidiaries"}, {"term": "Currency call option", "definition": "Right to buy foreign currency at a strike rate; used by importers and those expecting to receive foreign currency"}, {"term": "Currency put option", "definition": "Right to sell foreign currency at a strike rate; used by exporters and those expecting to pay foreign currency"}], "discussionQuestions": ["A Zambian supplier ships goods to a South African customer for ZAR 1 million, payment due in 60 days. Current spot rate: ZMW/ZAR 0.0680. 60-day forward rate: ZMW/ZAR 0.0650. The supplier expects the kwacha to weaken. Should the supplier hedge with a forward contract? Calculate the kwacha proceeds under both spot and forward scenarios.", "Compare the use of a forward contract vs. a USD put option for an importer expecting to pay USD 100,000 in 3 months. What are the key differences in risk and reward?"], "learningOutcomes": ["Distinguish between transaction, translation, and economic FX exposure", "Interpret bid-ask spreads and calculate cross rates between currency pairs", "Calculate forward exchange rates using interest rate parity formula", "Structure a forward contract to hedge a specific FX receivable or payable", "Compare the costs and benefits of forwards vs. futures vs. options for FX hedging", "Use currency futures to hedge a large transaction exposure and calculate gains/losses", "Design a collar strategy (combination of options) to cap downside while preserving upside", "Evaluate operational hedging strategies (netting, natural hedges, sourcing) and when each is appropriate", "Apply FX hedging techniques to Zambian corporations dealing in USD, ZAR, and other regional currencies"]}'::jsonb
where slug = 'fx-risk'
  and lesson_id = (select id from lessons where slug = 'risk' and course_id = (select id from courses where slug = 'treasury-management'));

update steps set content = '{"sections": [{"eyebrow": "OVERVIEW", "heading": "The Debt Management Function", "body": "Corporate debt is central to financing strategy. A company needs working capital, funds for expansion, equipment purchases, and working capital management. Debt (along with equity) provides the cash to do these things. But debt is not free — it has a cost, and that cost varies based on the source, term, and credit quality.\n\nThe treasury function manages debt in the company''s best interest. This means three things: minimise the cost of borrowing across all sources and maturities; manage the risk of debt — refinancing risk, interest rate risk, currency risk; and maintain continued access to credit at reasonable rates.\n\nThe trade-off between cost and risk is central to debt management. A cheaper source of funds might require a longer commitment (refinancing risk) or might be available only when needed least. Treasury must balance these forces constantly."}, {"eyebrow": "SOURCES", "heading": "Sources of Debt", "body": "Companies access funds from multiple sources. The choice of source depends on the amount needed, the duration, the company''s credit rating, and market conditions.\n\n1. Bank Loans. The most common form of corporate debt. Banks lend on a secured (collateral required) or unsecured basis, depending on the borrower''s creditworthiness. Loans can be fixed rate or variable rate (tied to a base rate like the Bank of Zambia repo rate). Short-term loans are overdrafts and short-term loans of 3-12 months; medium-term loans of 3-5 years are common for capital expenditure; secured loans carry lower rates because the lender has recourse to collateral.\n\n2. Bond / Debenture Issuance. Large corporates and governments issue bonds — long-term debt securities sold to investors. A bond is a promise to pay principal at maturity and interest (the coupon) at regular intervals. Bonds can be fixed or floating rate, secured or unsecured, convertible to equity (for corporates), or straight debt. Bonds typically mature in 3-20 years. Investors can hold to maturity or sell in the secondary market. Bond prices move inversely to interest rates — when rates rise, bond prices fall.\n\n3. Commercial Paper. Unsecured, short-term promissory notes issued by large, creditworthy companies. CP matures in 1-270 days, typically 30-90 days. It is issued at a discount to face value and carries lower rates than bank loans because it is short-term and issued by blue-chip companies. It must be renewed frequently (roll-over risk), is only available to large, highly-rated companies, and has an active secondary market that provides liquidity.\n\n4. Leasing. An alternative to debt financing for equipment. The company leases equipment from a lessor, paying rent over the lease term. This transfers the residual value risk to the lessor; the company avoids the upfront capital cost and obsolescence risk. An operating lease is short-term, flexible, and resembles a rental. A finance lease is long-term, effectively a purchase on credit.\n\n5. Hire Purchase. A form of instalment buying used for equipment. The finance company buys the equipment and the company hires it with an option to purchase at the end. Ownership transfers to the company once the final payment is made.", "callout": {"label": "Fact", "body": "Zambia context: Bank loans dominate corporate borrowing. Bonds are less common in Zambia due to shallow capital markets. However, the government regularly issues bonds domestically (ZMW and USD denominated). Commercial paper is rare. Leasing and hire purchase are used for equipment but less common than in developed markets."}}, {"eyebrow": "MATCHING", "heading": "Short-Term vs Long-Term Debt: The Matching Principle", "body": "A core principle in finance is the matching principle: the maturity of the source of funds should match the maturity of the use. Short-term assets should be financed with short-term debt; long-term assets with long-term debt.\n\nShort-Term Debt is used for: working capital (inventory, receivables), seasonal cash needs, temporary shortfalls. Advantages: lower interest rates (the yield curve is usually upward sloping); flexible — can be renewed or replaced with different terms; matches the duration of working capital needs. Disadvantages: refinancing risk — must find new funds when the loan matures; interest rate risk — rates may rise when the loan is renewed; overdraft availability may be cancelled at any time.\n\nLong-Term Debt is used for: capital expenditure, fixed assets, long-term financing. Advantages: certainty of funds — locked in for the full term; no refinancing risk; matches the life of the asset being financed. Disadvantages: higher interest rates; less flexibility — cannot be repaid early without penalty; commitment extends beyond the period for which funds may be needed."}, {"eyebrow": "COVENANTS", "heading": "Loan Covenants", "body": "A loan covenant is a restriction imposed by the lender on the borrower''s activities. Covenants protect the lender by constraining the borrower''s ability to take actions that might impair its ability to repay.\n\nAffirmative Covenants (the borrower must): maintain minimum working capital ratios or current ratios; maintain minimum interest coverage ratio (EBIT / Interest expense); provide quarterly or annual financial statements to the lender; maintain insurance on assets financed by the loan; pay all taxes on time.\n\nRestrictive Covenants (the borrower cannot): issue additional debt beyond a specified level without lender consent; dispose of assets financed by the loan; pay dividends if doing so would violate a debt-to-equity ratio; make capital expenditures above a certain amount; change the nature of the business without lender consent.\n\nViolations of covenants can trigger default, giving the lender the right to demand early repayment. This restriction on treasury''s flexibility is the cost of borrowing — the lower the lender''s risk, the lower the interest rate."}, {"eyebrow": "BONDS", "heading": "Bond Pricing & Valuation", "body": "When a company issues a bond, it specifies a coupon rate (the annual interest paid) and a face value (the principal repaid at maturity). The price at which the bond trades in the market depends on the market interest rate.\n\nBond Valuation Formula: Bond Price = C / (1 + r) + C / (1 + r)^2 + ... + (C + FV) / (1 + r)^n. Where C = annual coupon payment, r = market interest rate (yield), FV = face value (principal), and n = years to maturity.\n\nWorked Example: Zambian Corporate Bond. A Zambian manufacturing company issues a 5-year bond with face value K1,000,000, coupon rate 12% per annum (K120,000 paid annually). Current market yields for similar bonds are 14%. Discounting each cash flow at 14% gives: K120,000 / 1.14 = K105,263; K120,000 / 1.14^2 = K92,338; K120,000 / 1.14^3 = K80,996; K120,000 / 1.14^4 = K71,052; and (K120,000 + K1,000,000) / 1.14^5 = K651,451. Summing these gives a bond price of K1,001,100.\n\nThis is a puzzle worth noting: the bond appears worth slightly more than face value even though market yields (14%) exceed the coupon (12%) — normally that would price the bond below par. The underlying issue is that the bond is issued at par (K1,000,000) with a 12% coupon while market rates are 14% at the time of sale, so pricing it at par under-compensates investors. The company has two practical options: issue at a higher coupon of roughly 12.67% instead, or issue at face value but at a discount (investors pay around K989,000, the coupon stays at 12%, and the effective yield to investors is 14%). In practice, the company issues at par with a coupon set to yield 14% to investors.\n\nDuration and Interest Rate Risk. Duration measures how sensitive a bond''s price is to interest rate changes. A longer-duration bond (longer maturity, lower coupon) is more sensitive to rate changes. This is why long-term bond prices fall more sharply when rates rise than short-term bond prices do."}, {"eyebrow": "RATINGS", "heading": "Credit Ratings", "body": "Credit rating agencies (Moody''s, Standard & Poor''s, Fitch) assess the credit risk of borrowers. A rating reflects the agency''s judgment of the likelihood that the issuer will default on its obligations.\n\nThe rating scale runs from highest to lowest credit quality. AAA (S&P: Prime; Moody''s: Aaa) is the highest credit quality. AA (S&P: High Grade; Moody''s: Aa) is very high credit quality. A (S&P: Upper Medium Grade; Moody''s: A) is upper medium grade. BBB (S&P: Medium Grade; Moody''s: Baa) is medium grade. BB (S&P: Non-Investment Grade; Moody''s: Ba) is speculative. B (S&P: Highly Speculative; Moody''s: B) carries high default risk. CCC (S&P: In Default; Moody''s: Caa) is in or near default.\n\nInvestment grade (BBB and above) are considered safe for institutional investors. Below BBB is speculative grade — higher yield but higher default risk.\n\nZambia''s Sovereign Rating. Zambia''s sovereign credit rating affects the cost of borrowing for both government and corporates. A lower sovereign rating signals higher risk to international investors, which raises borrowing costs. Ratings are published by the three major agencies; they differ but move in the same direction. For students, the key insight is: credit ratings matter. A downgrade in a country''s rating can tighten credit markets and raise rates."}, {"eyebrow": "PORTFOLIO", "heading": "Debt Portfolio Management", "body": "A company''s debt portfolio includes all outstanding borrowings — bank loans, bonds, leases, hire purchases, trade credit. Treasury must manage the mix to minimise cost while managing refinancing risk and interest rate risk.\n\nMix of Fixed and Floating Rate Debt. Fixed rate debt locks in the cost. If rates rise, the company benefits. If rates fall, the company is locked in at the higher rate. Floating rate debt moves with rates. If rates rise, the company''s interest expense rises. If rates fall, it benefits. Treasury must decide what the right mix is. This depends on the company''s view of future rates, its ability to absorb rate increases (cash flow), and its risk tolerance. A company with stable, high cash flows can tolerate more floating rate debt. A company with volatile cash flows might prefer fixed.\n\nMaturity Profile. Treasury should manage the maturity profile of debt — the distribution of maturities across time. A company that borrows K10 million due in Year 1, K10 million in Year 2, and K10 million in Year 3 faces refinancing risk each year, but it avoids a large refinancing spike in a single year. A company that borrows K30 million due in Year 1 faces a large refinancing need — if market conditions deteriorate or the company''s credit rating drops, rolling over the debt becomes expensive or impossible."}, {"eyebrow": "RESTRUCTURING", "heading": "Debt Restructuring", "body": "When a company''s cash flows deteriorate or rates fall sharply, it may consider restructuring its debt — negotiating new terms with creditors. This might mean extending maturity, reducing the coupon, or converting debt to equity.\n\nRestructuring is preferable to default because it avoids the legal and reputational costs of default. But it signals financial stress and may damage the company''s credit rating."}], "keyTerms": [{"term": "Debt", "definition": "Money owed by a company to creditors, repayable with interest"}, {"term": "Loan covenant", "definition": "Restrictions imposed by a lender on the borrower''s activities"}, {"term": "Affirmative covenant", "definition": "A covenant that requires the borrower to take certain actions"}, {"term": "Restrictive covenant", "definition": "A covenant that prohibits the borrower from taking certain actions"}, {"term": "Bond", "definition": "A long-term debt security issued by a borrower and purchased by investors"}, {"term": "Coupon", "definition": "The annual interest paid on a bond, usually as a percentage of face value"}, {"term": "Face value", "definition": "The principal amount of a bond, repaid at maturity"}, {"term": "Yield", "definition": "The effective interest rate earned on a bond, based on the price paid"}, {"term": "Discount", "definition": "When a bond trades below face value (because market rates exceed coupon)"}, {"term": "Premium", "definition": "When a bond trades above face value (because coupon exceeds market rates)"}, {"term": "Duration", "definition": "A measure of how sensitive a bond''s price is to interest rate changes"}, {"term": "Commercial paper", "definition": "Short-term, unsecured promissory notes, typically 1-270 days"}, {"term": "Credit rating", "definition": "An assessment of creditworthiness issued by a rating agency"}, {"term": "Investment grade", "definition": "Credit rating of BBB or better; considered safe for institutional investors"}, {"term": "Speculative grade", "definition": "Credit rating below BBB; higher risk, higher yield"}, {"term": "Matching principle", "definition": "The duration of financing should match the duration of the use"}, {"term": "Refinancing risk", "definition": "The risk that a loan cannot be renewed on the same terms"}, {"term": "Debt restructuring", "definition": "Negotiating new terms with creditors to improve the borrower''s position"}], "discussionQuestions": ["A Zambian company has been offered bank financing at 18% on a 3-year loan, or a bond issuance with a 15% coupon. The company estimates its cost of equity at 20%. Why might the bond be cheaper? What risks does the company take on by issuing bonds instead of using bank loans?", "A company with a BBB credit rating approaches a bank for a 10-year loan. The bank proposes affirmative covenants (minimum interest coverage of 3.0x) and restrictive covenants (no additional debt without bank consent). How do these covenants protect the bank? How might they constrain the company''s treasury function?"], "learningOutcomes": ["Explain the objectives of debt management and the role of the treasurer", "Identify the main sources of corporate debt and their characteristics (cost, duration, flexibility)", "Apply the matching principle to choose between short-term and long-term debt", "Explain loan covenants and how they protect lenders while constraining borrower flexibility", "Price a bond given face value, coupon, market yield, and years to maturity", "Interpret credit ratings and explain their impact on borrowing costs", "Manage a debt portfolio by balancing fixed vs floating rate debt and maturity profiles", "Explain debt restructuring and when it might be appropriate"]}'::jsonb
where slug = 'debt-management'
  and lesson_id = (select id from lessons where slug = 'investment' and course_id = (select id from courses where slug = 'treasury-management'));

update steps set content = '{"sections": [{"eyebrow": "FOUNDATIONS", "heading": "Treasury Investment Objectives", "body": "Companies generate cash surpluses from operations, asset sales, and borrowing. This cash sits in bank accounts earning nothing until it''s needed. Treasury''s job is to invest these surpluses safely and profitably while maintaining liquidity.\n\nWhen investing surplus cash, treasury faces a hierarchy of objectives — not all equally important.\n\n1. Safety (Capital Preservation): The first rule is: don''t lose the principal. A loss of capital is a failure of treasury''s core function. This means avoiding default risk, credit risk, and unnecessary market risk. The safest investments — government bonds, bank deposits, money market funds — pay lower returns. But that''s the trade-off.\n\n2. Liquidity (Accessibility): Cash may be needed tomorrow for payroll, or in three months for a capital expenditure. Treasury must maintain a ladder of maturities so that funds are available when needed. This might mean passing up higher yields on longer-term instruments to keep funds in call deposits and short-term securities.\n\n3. Yield (Return on Investment): Only after safety and liquidity are satisfied does treasury pursue higher yields. Yield is the residual objective — you earn what the market will give you on the remaining surplus after meeting the other two goals.", "callout": {"label": "Warning", "body": "Key insight: The hierarchy is strict. Do not sacrifice safety for yield. Do not sacrifice liquidity for yield. Too many corporate treasurers have learned this the hard way by investing in high-yield instruments that defaulted or became illiquid during a crisis."}}, {"eyebrow": "POLICY", "heading": "Investment Policy Statement", "body": "A treasury investment policy is a written document that sets the rules for investment. It covers: approved instruments — which securities can treasury buy (e.g., T-bills only, or also bank CDs and corporate bonds); credit rating limits — minimum credit rating (e.g., no investment below BBB for corporates); counterparty limits — maximum exposure to any single bank or institution (concentration risk); maturity limits — maximum maturity allowed (e.g., no investments beyond 1 year for the operating reserve); diversification — how to spread risk across multiple issuers and instruments; reporting requirements — how treasury reports on investment performance to management/board; and review and approval process — who approves investment policy and how often it''s reviewed.\n\nThe policy is approved by the board of directors or the audit committee. It protects both treasury and the company — it removes discretion and sets clear guardrails. If an investment goes bad, treasury can point to the policy and say, ''We invested within the approved guidelines.''"}, {"eyebrow": "SHORT-TERM", "heading": "Short-Term Investment Instruments", "body": "Short-term instruments mature in less than one year. They are highly liquid and low-risk.\n\nTreasury Bills (ZMW): Issued by the Bank of Zambia (BoZ) on behalf of government. Bills mature in 91, 182, or 364 days. They are issued at a discount to par — you pay K99 for a K100 bill due in 91 days, earning K1 = 1.01% yield. T-bills are the safest investment available in Zambia (backed by government); they are also the most liquid (active secondary market). The downside: T-bill yields are usually the lowest available. In 2023–2024, BoZ T-bills yielded 25–27% due to inflation fighting; this is unusually high for Zambia.\n\nCall Deposits: Current accounts at commercial banks that pay interest. The bank can require 7 or 30 days'' notice before withdrawal, but in practice, money is available on request. Rates are lower than term deposits (the price of flexibility) but higher than cash in a non-interest-bearing account. Call deposits carry credit risk — the bank could fail — but this risk is typically rated as low for major Zambian banks.\n\nTerm Deposits: Fixed-term deposits (30, 60, 90, 120 days) at commercial banks. Rates increase with term length (the yield curve is upward sloping). Early withdrawal is usually not permitted, or it incurs a penalty. These are suitable for cash forecasted to be available for the full term.\n\nMoney Market Funds: Pooled investments in T-bills, call deposits, and commercial paper. A money market fund offers instant liquidity, professional management, and diversification. The fund manager invests your cash in a mix of instruments; you can withdraw at any time at net asset value (NAV). Returns fluctuate based on the underlying instruments. Money market funds are common in developed markets; they''re less common in Zambia but growing."}, {"eyebrow": "MEDIUM-TERM", "heading": "Medium-Term Investment Instruments", "body": "Medium-term instruments mature in 1-5 years. They offer higher yields than short-term instruments but carry more interest rate risk.\n\nBonds: Government and corporate bonds with maturity of 2-10 years. They pay regular coupons (interest) and return principal at maturity. Bond prices move inversely to market interest rates — if rates rise, bond prices fall. This creates market risk for treasury if it needs to sell before maturity. However, if treasury holds to maturity, the price fluctuation doesn''t matter.\n\nBond Yield Calculation: Bonds are quoted by their yield, not their price. The yield accounts for the coupon, the purchase price, and the time to maturity.\n\nYield to Maturity (YTM) is the internal rate of return on the bond given the purchase price. Example: a 5-year government bond with 8% coupon, face value K1,000,000. If purchased at par (K1,000,000), YTM = 8%. If purchased at discount (K950,000), YTM is greater than 8% (the lower price increases the return). If purchased at premium (K1,050,000), YTM is less than 8% (the higher price reduces the return)."}, {"eyebrow": "CREDIT", "heading": "Credit Risk & Diversification", "body": "When treasury invests in instruments issued by banks or corporations, it faces credit risk — the risk that the issuer defaults. Government bonds (in a stable country) carry negligible credit risk. Bank deposits carry credit risk equal to the bank''s solvency. Corporate bonds carry higher credit risk based on the company''s credit rating.\n\nCounterparty Limits: An investment policy typically sets a limit on exposure to any single bank or issuer. For example: no more than 20% of investable cash with any single bank; no corporate bonds below A rating; no single issuer to receive more than K500,000.\n\nDiversification: Spreading investments across multiple instruments and issuers reduces concentration risk. A portfolio of 50% T-bills, 30% call deposits across 3 banks, and 20% in short-dated corporate bonds is more diversified than 100% in one bank CD."}, {"eyebrow": "CONSTRUCTION", "heading": "Portfolio Construction Strategies", "body": "Treasury uses several approaches to structure an investment portfolio. Each has different risk and return characteristics.\n\nLaddering Strategy: Create a ladder of maturities — equal amounts invested in 1-month, 3-month, 6-month, and 12-month instruments. Each month/quarter, as the shortest-maturity instrument matures, reinvest it in the longest-maturity allowed by the policy. This maintains constant liquidity while capturing the yield curve''s upward slope.\n\nBullet Strategy: Invest all funds in instruments maturing on a specific future date — e.g., all in 6-month bonds. This matches a known cash need. If cash is needed in 6 months, buying all 6-month instruments guarantees the funds will be available. The downside: no portfolio rebalancing, and if rates rise sharply, you''re locked in at the lower rate.\n\nBarbell Strategy: Invest in both short-term and long-term instruments (the ''barbell''), avoiding medium-term instruments. For example, 60% in 30-day deposits and 40% in 3-year bonds. This provides both liquidity and yield. It works well if you expect rates to move — if rates fall, the long bonds appreciate; if rates rise, the short-term reinvests at higher rates."}, {"eyebrow": "EXAMPLE", "heading": "Worked Example: Building a Portfolio", "body": "Scenario: A Zambian manufacturer has ZMW 5 million surplus cash. The treasurer forecasts that K2 million will be needed in 3 months (quarterly tax payment), K1.5 million in 6 months (dividend payment), and K1.5 million will be available for the full 12 months. The investment policy allows T-bills, bank CDs, call deposits (minimum credit rating A), and short-dated government bonds (maximum 2-year maturity).\n\nCurrent Yields: call deposit at Bank A, on-demand, yields 10%; term deposit at Bank A, 30 days, yields 11%; term deposit at Bank A, 90 days, yields 12%; T-bill, 91 days, yields 13%; T-bill, 182 days, yields 14%; government bond, 1 year, yields 15%; government bond, 2 year, yields 16%.\n\nPortfolio Construction — Tranche 1 (Liquidity reserve, K500,000): available for immediate use (contingencies, payroll). Invest in call deposits at 10%. Annual yield = K50,000.\n\nTranche 2 (Due in 3 months, K2,000,000): needed for tax payment. Invest in 91-day T-bill at 13%. Annual yield = K260,000.\n\nTranche 3 (Due in 6 months, K1,500,000): needed for dividend. Invest in 182-day T-bill at 14%. Annual yield = K210,000.\n\nTranche 4 (Full 12 months, K1,000,000): available for the long term. Invest in 1-year government bond at 15%. Annual yield = K150,000.\n\nTotal invested: K5,000,000. Total annual yield: K50,000 + K260,000 + K210,000 + K150,000 = K670,000. Blended yield: K670,000 ÷ K5,000,000 = 13.4%. Note: the portfolio yields 13.4% while maintaining complete matching of cash needs with maturities."}, {"eyebrow": "PERFORMANCE", "heading": "Performance Measurement", "body": "Treasury''s investment performance is measured against a benchmark. The benchmark is typically the weighted average of relevant market yields. For example, a portfolio invested 40% in 91-day T-bills and 60% in 1-year bonds should be measured against a benchmark weighted the same way.\n\nTotal Return: total return includes coupon income plus any capital gains or losses from mark-to-market revaluation. For a buy-and-hold portfolio, total return equals the yield at purchase.\n\nPerformance Monitoring: treasury reports on performance quarterly or annually, comparing realized return to the benchmark. Large deviations from the benchmark signal either skill or excessive risk-taking."}], "keyTerms": [{"term": "Treasury investment", "definition": "The deployment of surplus cash into securities to earn returns while preserving capital"}, {"term": "Safety (capital preservation)", "definition": "The primary objective: avoid loss of principal through default or imprudent risk"}, {"term": "Liquidity", "definition": "The ability to access cash when needed; a co-primary objective"}, {"term": "Yield", "definition": "The return earned on an investment, subordinate to safety and liquidity"}, {"term": "Investment policy statement", "definition": "A written document setting approved instruments, limits, and controls for treasury investment"}, {"term": "Credit rating limit", "definition": "A minimum acceptable credit rating for investment (e.g., no bonds below BBB)"}, {"term": "Counterparty limit", "definition": "A maximum exposure to any single issuer or institution"}, {"term": "Treasury bill", "definition": "Short-term government debt, issued at discount, maturity up to 1 year"}, {"term": "Call deposit", "definition": "Interest-bearing current account requiring notice (or not, in practice) before withdrawal"}, {"term": "Term deposit", "definition": "Fixed-term bank deposit at a fixed rate, maturity up to 12 months, no early withdrawal"}, {"term": "Money market fund", "definition": "A pooled investment in short-term instruments, offering liquidity and diversification"}, {"term": "Government bond", "definition": "Long-term debt issued by government, paying coupon, maturity 1-10+ years"}, {"term": "Yield to maturity (YTM)", "definition": "The effective return on a bond, accounting for coupon, price, and time to maturity"}, {"term": "Market risk", "definition": "The risk that a bond''s price falls due to rising market interest rates"}, {"term": "Concentration risk", "definition": "The risk from overexposure to a single issuer or instrument"}, {"term": "Laddering", "definition": "A portfolio strategy using equal amounts across a range of maturities"}, {"term": "Bullet strategy", "definition": "Concentrating investments in a single maturity matching a known cash need"}, {"term": "Barbell strategy", "definition": "Investing in short-term and long-term instruments, avoiding the middle"}, {"term": "Total return", "definition": "Coupon income plus capital gains/losses from mark-to-market revaluation"}], "discussionQuestions": ["A company has ZMW 3 million available for investment for 6 months. Current 6-month T-bill yields 12%; 6-month term deposit at Bank X (rating A) yields 13%; 6-month corporate bond (rating BBB) yields 15%. The company''s investment policy prohibits corporate bonds below A. Which instrument should treasury choose? What is the expected return?", "Explain the trade-off between a laddering strategy (maintaining constant maturities) and a bullet strategy (concentrating investments in a single maturity). When is each appropriate?"], "learningOutcomes": ["Explain the three-tier hierarchy of treasury investment objectives (safety, liquidity, yield) and why the order matters", "Design an investment policy statement covering approved instruments, credit limits, maturity limits, and diversification", "Calculate yields on treasury bills and bonds; evaluate which instruments to select based on forecast cash needs", "Construct a portfolio using a laddering, bullet, or barbell strategy, matching investment maturities to cash forecasts", "Assess credit risk and set counterparty limits to prevent concentration risk", "Explain the trade-off between yield and liquidity in investment selection", "Measure portfolio performance against a benchmark and explain deviations"]}'::jsonb
where slug = 'investment-management'
  and lesson_id = (select id from lessons where slug = 'investment' and course_id = (select id from courses where slug = 'treasury-management'));

update steps set content = '{"sections": [{"eyebrow": "FOUNDATIONS", "heading": "What is Clearing and Settlement?", "body": "Clearing and settlement are two distinct stages in the payment process that work together to move value from one party to another. Many people use these terms interchangeably, but treasury professionals must understand the difference.\n\nClearing is all the steps involved in transferring ownership of funds from one party to another — except the final step. It covers everything from the moment a payment instruction is issued to the moment the money is about to change hands. Clearing includes validation of payment details, matching of sender and receiver accounts, and preparation of settlement instructions.\n\nSettlement is the finalization of the payment. It''s the moment when the funds actually transfer, when a new party takes possession of the money, when the accounts are debited and credited, and when the transaction becomes final and irrevocable. Settlement is the point at which the risk ends: both parties have received what they expected.", "callout": {"label": "Fact", "body": "For treasury: Understanding clearing vs settlement matters because risk exists during clearing. Until settlement is complete, either party could fail, leaving the other exposed. This is why settlement systems are carefully managed."}}, {"eyebrow": "RISK", "heading": "Settlement Risk and Herstatt Risk", "body": "Settlement risk is the risk that one party to a transaction fails before settlement is complete, leaving the other party exposed. It''s particularly acute in foreign exchange transactions because FX settlements occur in two different countries at different times.\n\nWhen a company trades EUR for USD, one bank must settle euros in Frankfurt (on European time), and another must settle dollars in New York (on US time). Because the time zones are different, one side of the transaction settles hours before the other. For example, euros settle first (during Frankfurt business hours), but dollars settle later (New York is 6 hours behind). If the counterparty fails after sending euros but before sending dollars, the company loses the euros and never receives the dollars.\n\nHerstatt risk gets its name from Herstatt Bank, a German bank that failed in 1974 during the Bretton Woods era. Herstatt had entered into foreign exchange transactions, received payments in deutsche marks, but failed to deliver dollars to counterparties. The bank''s collapse left counterparties with losses — they had sent deutschmarks but never received dollars. This single failure highlighted a systemic risk in the global payment system and prompted regulators to build safer settlement infrastructure.", "callout": {"label": "Warning", "body": "Still relevant today: Herstatt risk is why the CLS Bank system exists (discussed below). Every large FX transaction today is routed through CLS to eliminate the timing gap that made Herstatt possible."}}, {"eyebrow": "SETTLEMENT TYPES", "heading": "Gross Settlement vs Net Settlement", "body": "There are two main ways to settle payments: gross basis and net basis. The choice depends on the size of the transaction, its urgency, and cost tolerance.\n\nIn gross settlement, each payment is settled individually and in full. Bank A pays the full amount owed to Bank B for each transaction separately, and the transaction is final immediately. This is Real-Time Gross Settlement (RTGS) — transactions are processed in real time, one by one, settled individually and immediately. It is used for high-value payments and time-critical transactions such as securities trades and large corporate payments. Cost is high, since each transaction incurs bank fees. Liquidity requirement is high, since banks must have funds pre-positioned to settle each transaction. Risk is lower, because payment is final immediately with no unsettled exposure overnight.\n\nIn net settlement, transactions are accumulated throughout the day, then offset against each other. Only the net difference between banks is settled. For example, if Bank A owes Bank B K100m but Bank B owes Bank A K80m, only K20m changes hands — the net position. This is Deferred Net Settlement (DNS) — settlement waits until the end of the day. It is used for lower-value payments and routine transactions such as utility bills, payroll, and interbank transfers. Cost is low, since many transactions offset, reducing the number of actual fund transfers. Liquidity requirement is low, since only net amounts need to be transferred. Risk is higher, since many unsettled transactions sit overnight, creating exposure if a bank fails.", "callout": {"label": "Fact", "body": "Choice depends on transaction size: High-value payments must use RTGS (gross) because the risk of overnight exposure is too great. Low-value payments can wait for end-of-day netting (DNS) because the cost savings outweigh the risk."}}, {"eyebrow": "INFRASTRUCTURE", "heading": "SWIFT — The Global Payment Messaging System", "body": "SWIFT (Society for Worldwide Interbank Financial Telecommunications) is a secure, standardized messaging network used by banks worldwide to exchange payment instructions. SWIFT doesn''t move money; it carries the messages that instruct banks to move money.\n\nKey SWIFT message types: MT103 is used for customer credit transfers, for example when a company sends a payment instruction to its bank. MT202 is used for bank-to-bank transfers, where banks settle accounts with each other — this is core for RTGS. MT300 is used for FX trade confirmation, where banks confirm FX deal terms. MT320 is used to instruct settlement of securities, such as bond or share trades.\n\nLarge corporates can connect directly to the SWIFT network through their banks. Treasury staff can initiate payments, confirm FX trades, and instruct securities settlements directly. Smaller firms send instructions to their bank, which translates them into SWIFT messages. SWIFT messages are standardized (same format worldwide), highly secure, and legally binding. SWIFT uses encryption and digital signatures to prevent fraud. Most banks worldwide are SWIFT members, including all major Zambian banks. Every message is timestamped and logged, which is essential for compliance and dispute resolution."}, {"eyebrow": "FX SETTLEMENT", "heading": "CLS Bank: Eliminating Herstatt Risk", "body": "CLS Bank International was created to solve the Herstatt problem. It''s a central counterparty that stands in the middle of every FX trade settled through it, ensuring that both sides of the transaction settle simultaneously.\n\nHow CLS works: Company A and Bank A agree to trade EUR for USD (bilateral payment). Both sides send settlement instructions to CLS. Both banks pre-fund CLS accounts in their local currencies. CLS then debits Bank A''s EUR account and credits its USD account at the exact same moment (simultaneous settlement). Because CLS is the buyer to one side and the seller to the other, the counterparty risk is eliminated — neither bank faces the other''s credit risk.\n\nCLS eliminates the timing gap that made Herstatt possible. Because settlement is simultaneous in both currencies, neither party can fail after receiving one side of the trade without settling the other. This is called Payment versus Payment (PvP) — the exchange happens atomically. Today, nearly all major FX trades flow through CLS.", "callout": {"label": "Note", "body": "For treasury: When you trade FX with CLS settlement, you eliminate Herstatt risk. Your bank will default to CLS settlement for most currency pairs. Insist on it — it''s safer and has become the market standard."}}, {"eyebrow": "SECURITIES", "heading": "Delivery versus Payment (DvP)", "body": "When a company buys or sells securities (bonds, shares, T-bills), the same timing risk exists: one side settles (securities move) before the other (cash moves). Delivery versus Payment (DvP) is the securities equivalent of CLS''s PvP.\n\nA ''fail'' occurs when one party delivers securities but the other fails to pay, or vice versa. For example, a company buys K10m of government bonds and the seller delivers them, but the seller''s bank fails before paying. The buyer holds the bonds but never received the cash. DvP systems synchronise both transfers so this can''t happen.\n\nA central securities depository (CSD) or central counterparty (CCP) sits between buyers and sellers. It uses the same simultaneous settlement principle as CLS: securities are transferred from seller to buyer''s account in the depository, and cash is transferred from buyer to seller''s bank in the settlement system — both at the exact same moment. If either side fails, neither transfer completes.", "callout": {"label": "Fact", "body": "Clearing and settlement of securities: Clearing involves matching and confirmation of the trade. Settlement (DvP) involves simultaneous transfer of cash and securities. This is why securities trades take 1–2 days to settle (T+1 or T+2) rather than instantly — settlement infrastructure takes time to process."}}, {"eyebrow": "LOCAL SYSTEMS", "heading": "Zambia''s Electronic Payment Systems", "body": "The Bank of Zambia oversees systemically important payment systems (SIPS) — systems whose failure could trigger wider economic problems. Three major systems handle payments in Zambia: ZIPSS (RTGS), EFT (deferred net), and CIC (cheque clearing).\n\nZIPSS (Zambia Interbank Payment and Settlement System) is a real-time gross settlement system operated by the Bank of Zambia. It''s used for high-value, time-critical payments: VAT remittances, securities trading, large interbank transfers. Transactions are settled continuously in real time, with each transaction final immediately. Banks must pre-fund ZIPSS accounts; no overdrafts are allowed. Settlement risk is negligible because pre-funding and real-time settlement eliminate counterparty exposure. Banks can track their ZIPSS balance throughout the day. ZIPSS accepts both small and large payments; there are no minimum or maximum transaction amounts.\n\nEFT (Electronic Funds Transfer) is a deferred net settlement system for routine, lower-value payments. Common uses include wage and salary payments, utility bills, tax payments, and loan disbursements. Transactions are batched daily and settled at the end of the day. Funds typically credit within the same day. Amount limits are higher than cheques but lower than ZIPSS. Payments are guaranteed by commercial banks and the system is safe and secure. Almost all commercial banks in Zambia participate.\n\nCIC (Cheque Image Clearing System) is a cheque clearing system using cheque truncation (CTS). Instead of physically moving paper cheques between banks, cheques are scanned into digital images, which are cleared electronically. This is faster and lower-risk than handling physical paper. Settlement speed is T+1 (one clearing day) — a vast improvement from the old T+3. Risk is reduced since there is no manual handling or physical transport of cheques, so cheques can''t be lost in transit. Cash flow velocity improves for businesses, since cheques clear in one day instead of three. CTS has standardized the clearing period across Zambia.", "callout": {"label": "Warning", "body": "For Zambian treasury: Choose ZIPSS for urgent, high-value payments (securities, VAT, urgent corporate payments). Use EFT for routine, lower-value payments (payroll, routine supplier payments). Cheques are still accepted but are slower and riskier; they''re being phased out in favour of electronic payments."}}, {"eyebrow": "INFRASTRUCTURE", "heading": "Central Counterparties (CCPs)", "body": "A central counterparty is an institution that stands between all buyers and sellers in a market. For every trade, the CCP becomes the buyer to the seller and the seller to the buyer. This mutualization of counterparty risk is what allows modern financial markets to function.\n\nExamples of CCPs: CLS Bank handles FX settlement. LCH Group handles derivatives clearing (interest rate swaps, currency swaps). National securities depositories handle securities settlement (DvP).\n\nInstead of Company A worrying about Company B''s creditworthiness (will they pay?), Company A only worries about the CCP''s creditworthiness (which is usually the strongest party in the chain because it''s regulated and well-capitalized). The CCP manages the risk through daily mark-to-market, daily margin collection, and default fund capital."}, {"eyebrow": "CONVENTIONS", "heading": "Settlement Timing: T+1, T+2, and When It Matters", "body": "T+0 means same-day settlement. T+1 means settlement one business day after the trade. T+2 means two business days after. These are conventions — agreed standards across the market.\n\nClearing takes time. Trades must be validated, matched, confirmed. Documentation must be prepared. Settlement instructions must be routed through banks and payment systems. For most securities, T+2 (two business days) is the standard because that''s how long these steps take. Zambia''s cheque system uses T+1 because electronic clearing is faster than the old physical sorting.\n\nIf a trade fails to settle on time (say, securities don''t arrive when cash is due), both parties suffer. The buyer has cash but no securities; the seller has securities but no cash. Modern settlement systems impose penalties for fails — the failing party must pay interest or a fine. This incentivizes everyone to settle on time."}, {"eyebrow": "OPERATIONS", "heading": "Treasury Cut-Off Times and Daylight Overdrafts", "body": "Each payment system has a cut-off time — after which transactions submitted that day won''t settle until the next day. Treasury staff must understand these cut-offs to ensure payments settle when promised.\n\nIf a company promises to pay a customer by 2 pm, it must submit the SWIFT payment instruction before the bank''s cut-off time (often noon or 1 pm). Submitting after cut-off means the payment won''t settle until the next day — the promise is broken. Missed cut-offs are a major source of disputes and relationship damage.\n\nA daylight overdraft occurs when a bank allows a customer''s account to go negative during the day, with the expectation that the account will be funded before the end of the day. Example: A company has K5m in its account at 8 am. It receives invoices totalling K12m due by 4 pm. It makes all the payments using the bank''s daylight facility (allowing a K7m overdraft), and by 5 pm it has received K15m in customer collections, bringing its account to K8m positive. The account was never in overdraft at the end of the day. Banks charge fees for daylight overdrafts because they carry intraday settlement risk."}, {"eyebrow": "INTEGRATION", "heading": "How Settlement Connects to Earlier Steps", "body": "Step 3.2 — FX Risk: FX forwards, money market hedges, and FX options are all settled through CLS or similar systems. Understanding settlement risk and PvP is essential to understanding why CLS exists and how to use it safely.\n\nStep 4.2 — Investment Management: Treasury invests in T-bills, bonds, and other securities. All of these settle via DvP systems. Understanding settlement conventions (T+1, T+2) is essential to cash planning — cash isn''t actually available until settlement completes, not when a purchase order is placed.\n\nWhen Step 5.2 (Treasury Systems) integrates all these steps, the TMS must track not just deals, but settlement status — which trades have cleared, which are awaiting settlement, which have failed."}], "keyTerms": [{"term": "Clearing", "definition": "All steps in a payment transaction except final settlement"}, {"term": "Settlement", "definition": "Final transfer of funds; the point at which risk ends"}, {"term": "Settlement risk", "definition": "Risk that one party fails during clearing, before settlement completes"}, {"term": "Herstatt risk", "definition": "Settlement risk specific to FX; named after the 1974 Herstatt Bank failure"}, {"term": "Gross settlement (RTGS)", "definition": "Individual transactions settled one by one, immediately, in full"}, {"term": "Net settlement (DNS)", "definition": "Transactions offset against each other; only net difference settled"}, {"term": "SWIFT", "definition": "Global secure messaging network for bank-to-bank payment instructions"}, {"term": "MT103", "definition": "SWIFT message for customer credit transfer (payment instruction)"}, {"term": "MT202", "definition": "SWIFT message for bank-to-bank transfer"}, {"term": "CLS Bank", "definition": "Central counterparty for FX settlement; eliminates Herstatt risk"}, {"term": "Payment versus Payment (PvP)", "definition": "Simultaneous settlement of both sides of an FX trade"}, {"term": "Delivery versus Payment (DvP)", "definition": "Simultaneous settlement of securities and cash"}, {"term": "ZIPSS", "definition": "Zambia''s real-time gross settlement system (high-value payments)"}, {"term": "EFT", "definition": "Zambia''s electronic funds transfer system (routine, lower-value payments)"}, {"term": "Cheque Image Clearing (CIC)", "definition": "Zambia''s cheque clearing system using digital truncation (T+1)"}, {"term": "T+1, T+2", "definition": "Settlement timing conventions (T+1 = one business day after trade)"}, {"term": "Fail", "definition": "Failure to settle a trade on time; incurs penalties and interest"}, {"term": "Cut-off time", "definition": "Latest time to submit payment instructions for same-day settlement"}, {"term": "Daylight overdraft", "definition": "Negative account balance during the day, expected to be positive by end of day"}, {"term": "Central counterparty (CCP)", "definition": "Institution that sits between all buyers and sellers, mutualized risk"}], "discussionQuestions": ["A company uses RTGS for all payments above K5m and EFT for everything below. Why does this make sense? What risk is RTGS protecting against that EFT doesn''t?", "A company buys government bonds at 4 pm with T+2 settlement. When should it expect the cash to leave its bank account? What could go wrong between trade and settlement?"], "learningOutcomes": ["Distinguish between clearing and settlement and explain why the distinction matters for risk management", "Identify settlement risk (Herstatt risk) in FX transactions and explain how CLS eliminates it", "Distinguish between gross settlement (RTGS) and net settlement (DNS), and identify which is appropriate for a given transaction", "Explain how SWIFT enables bank-to-bank and customer-to-bank payments; name and describe key SWIFT message types", "Describe how CLS Bank and Payment versus Payment (PvP) eliminate FX settlement risk", "Explain how Delivery versus Payment (DvP) works in securities settlement and why it prevents settlement fails", "Identify the three major Zambian payment systems (ZIPSS, EFT, CIC) and describe their use cases, settlement timing, and risk profiles", "Explain the role of cut-off times and daylight overdrafts in treasury operations and cash management"]}'::jsonb
where slug = 'clearing-settlement'
  and lesson_id = (select id from lessons where slug = 'systems' and course_id = (select id from courses where slug = 'treasury-management'));

update steps set content = '{"sections": [{"eyebrow": "FOUNDATIONS", "heading": "What is a Treasury Management System (TMS)?", "body": "A Treasury Management System is a software application that automates the core functions of a treasury department. It integrates information from banks, market data providers, the company''s ERP system, and internal reporting tools, and presents that information in real time so treasury staff can make informed decisions.\n\nWhy Separate from ERP? Enterprise Resource Planning (ERP) systems like SAP are designed for the whole company: accounting, payroll, inventory, manufacturing. They''re excellent at tracking transactions for the official accounting ledger. But treasury has specific needs that ERPs don''t handle well: real-time cash visibility across multiple banks and currencies; FX trading, position tracking, and hedge accounting; deal capture and marking-to-market of derivatives; settlement and reconciliation of high-value financial transactions; and counterparty risk monitoring and exposure aggregation.\n\nA TMS fills these gaps. It''s built for the speed, precision, and risk visibility that treasury requires."}, {"eyebrow": "ARCHITECTURE", "heading": "Core TMS Functions", "body": "1. Deal Capture: When a treasury professional completes a deal (borrows at a rate, sells FX, invests in a bond, enters a swap), the deal is entered into the TMS once. The TMS records the full deal terms: counterparty, amount, rate, maturity, settlement instructions. This single entry feeds into all downstream processes.\n\n2. Position Management: The TMS aggregates all deals into positions. Cash position: total cash across all bank accounts, all currencies, all business units. FX position: net long or short in EUR, GBP, JPY, etc. Debt position: amount borrowed, by counterparty, by tenor. Investment position: what securities are held, at what cost, at what current value.\n\n3. Risk Analytics: The TMS calculates Value at Risk (VaR), duration, key rate durations, FX exposure, interest rate sensitivity, and counterparty exposure. It compares actual positions against policy limits and alerts treasury if limits are breached.\n\n4. Settlement and Reconciliation: The TMS tracks deals from inception through clearing and settlement. It knows which trades have settled, which are pending, which have failed. It matches bank confirmations against deal records to catch discrepancies.\n\n5. Reporting and Dashboard: The TMS provides real-time dashboards showing cash position, portfolio composition, risk metrics, and deal pipeline. Reports can be generated for management, board, auditors, and regulatory compliance. Custom reports can drill down to individual transactions.", "callout": {"label": "Fact", "body": "The common thread: All of these functions revolve around speed and accuracy. A TMS eliminates manual entry, reduces errors, and gives treasury the visibility it needs to manage risk in real time."}}, {"eyebrow": "CASH MANAGEMENT", "heading": "Cash Positioning in a TMS", "body": "One of the TMS''s most critical functions is aggregating the cash position. A multinational company might have 50+ bank accounts across 20 countries, in 10 different currencies. The TMS collects real-time balance data from each bank (via SWIFT, APIs, or bank portals) and presents a single consolidated view.\n\nWhat the TMS Shows: total cash by currency (how much USD, EUR, GBP, ZMW, etc. the company holds globally); total cash by bank (how much the company holds with each bank relationship); total unallocated cash (cash not yet allocated to specific uses, available for investment or transfers); and forecast cash position (projected cash over the next 10, 30, 90 days based on payment obligations and expected collections).\n\nWhy This Matters: Without a TMS, a treasurer managing 50 accounts has to log into each bank portal separately, write down the balance, convert it to a base currency, and manually compile a spreadsheet. This takes hours and is error-prone. With a TMS, the position updates automatically in real time. The treasurer sees it on a dashboard and can make investment or borrowing decisions immediately."}, {"eyebrow": "CONNECTIVITY", "heading": "TMS Bank Connectivity and Data Feeds", "body": "The TMS connects to banks in multiple ways to pull in data and push out payment instructions.\n\nSWIFT: Large corporates connect directly to SWIFT through a bank. The TMS sends outgoing payment instructions and receives incoming confirmations via SWIFT MT messages. This is the standard for high-value and international payments.\n\nHost-to-Host (Direct Bank Links): Some banks offer direct data feeds to customer systems. The bank and the company maintain a secure connection; the TMS polls for new balances, confirmations, and bank advice. This is faster than SWIFT for routine, lower-value transactions.\n\nOpen Banking APIs: Modern banks and fintech providers offer REST APIs for balance inquiry, payment initiation, and transaction history. Some TMSs now support these APIs, allowing easier integration with banks that haven''t yet implemented SWIFT or host-to-host.\n\nMarket Data Feeds: For risk analytics and deal pricing, the TMS receives real-time market data from Bloomberg, Reuters, or other providers. Interest rates, FX rates, credit spreads — the TMS uses this data to mark positions to market and calculate VaR."}, {"eyebrow": "STRUCTURE", "heading": "Front, Middle, Back Office in a TMS", "body": "A TMS is often organized into three functional areas, mirroring the organizational structure of treasury itself.\n\nFront Office: Deal makers'' interface. Dealers enter new deals: FX trades, interest rate swaps, bond purchases, lending decisions. The front office module gives pricing tools, comparative quotes, and deal booking functionality.\n\nMiddle Office: Risk and control layer. The middle office monitors positions, calculates risk, checks limits, and enforces policy. It flags deals that exceed counterparty exposure limits, VaR thresholds, or duration targets. Large trades may require middle office approval before they settle.\n\nBack Office: Operations and settlement. The back office processes confirmations, reconciles trades to bank statements, manages settlement instructions, and tracks fails. It''s the executor of the front office''s decisions and the validator of the middle office''s controls."}, {"eyebrow": "SELECTION", "heading": "Choosing a TMS: Build vs Buy", "body": "Build (Custom Development): Some large corporations build proprietary TMS software tailored to their exact processes. Advantages: perfect fit to the company''s workflow, competitive advantage if the system is unique. Disadvantages: extremely expensive (millions of pounds/dollars), takes years, requires large IT teams, constant maintenance, and the system becomes obsolete as the market evolves.\n\nBuy (Commercial TMS): Most companies purchase a commercial TMS. Major vendors include: Kyriba, owned by Wolters Kluwer, used for global mid-market to enterprise cash and liquidity management. FIS (Findynvest), owned by FIS, used for large enterprise derivatives and debt/investment management. ION Treasury, owned by ION Analytics, used for institutional and corporate treasury systems. SAP Treasury and Risk Management (TRM), owned by SAP, integrated with SAP ERP for mid-market to enterprise. Temenos, owned by Temenos, used for banking and treasury operations for banks.\n\nSelection Criteria: scope (does it cover all treasury functions you need — cash, FX, derivatives, debt, investments, settlement?); scalability (does it grow with your company and add more bank relationships without major rework?); integration (how easily does it connect to your ERP, banks, and market data providers?); configurability (can you customize workflows to match your processes without heavy custom coding?); user adoption (is the interface intuitive — will your team use it or stick to spreadsheets?); cost (implementation, licensing, annual fees — what''s the total cost of ownership?); and vendor stability (is the vendor financially stable and committed to the product?)."}, {"eyebrow": "IMPLEMENTATION", "heading": "TMS Implementation: Common Challenges", "body": "Data Migration: Moving historical transaction data from the old system (often spreadsheets or a legacy system) into the new TMS is painstaking. Data must be validated, cleaned, and mapped to the new system''s data structure. Errors here will haunt you for years.\n\nBank and System Integration: Connecting the TMS to each bank, the ERP, and market data providers requires custom work. Each connection is unique. Each bank has different APIs, message formats, and response times. Integration often takes longer than expected and costs more than budgeted.\n\nUser Adoption: Treasury staff who''ve been using Excel for years may resist the TMS. Training is essential, but even well-trained teams can be slow to change. If users don''t embrace the TMS, they''ll use it only partially, creating data quality issues and missing the benefits.\n\nComplexity: A full-featured TMS is complex. Most companies use only a fraction of its capabilities in year one. It''s tempting to disable features that seem unnecessary, but this can cause problems later when the company wants to expand treasury activities. Thorough training and change management are essential.", "callout": {"label": "Warning", "body": "Rule of thumb: Budget 30% for software, 70% for implementation (including data migration, integration, testing, and training). Budget 18–24 months for a full implementation in a large, complex organization."}}, {"eyebrow": "CONTROL", "heading": "How a TMS Enforces Treasury Policy", "body": "A TMS is the enforcement mechanism for treasury policy. Policy statements like ''We will not exceed 30% debt-to-equity'' or ''No counterparty shall exceed USD 100m exposure'' must be built into the system as hard rules or soft warnings.\n\nHard Limits: A hard limit blocks the transaction entirely. Example: A dealer tries to sell USD 150m of FX to a counterparty with an existing exposure of USD 80m, and the policy limit is USD 100m per counterparty. The TMS rejects the deal outright.\n\nSoft Limits (Warnings): A soft limit allows the transaction but requires approval. Example: A deal would bring counterparty exposure to USD 95m (below the USD 100m limit). The TMS allows it but logs it and notifies the treasurer. If a second deal comes along that would exceed the limit, it needs treasury head approval.\n\nExamples of Policies Enforced: counterparty exposure limits (no more than USD X with any single counterparty); tenor limits (maximum maturity of debt or swaps the company will enter); currency limits (maximum net long/short exposure in any currency); VaR limits (99th percentile Value at Risk cannot exceed USD X); leverage ratios (total debt cannot exceed X times EBITDA); and deal approval workflows (deals above USD X require CFO approval; deals above USD Y require CEO approval)."}, {"eyebrow": "BUSINESS CASE", "heading": "ROI of a Treasury Management System", "body": "A TMS is expensive, but the benefits can justify the cost. Here are the quantifiable returns.\n\nError Reduction: Manual spreadsheets cause errors: transposition errors, missing payments, double-payments, bank reconciliation mismatches. A TMS eliminates redundant data entry (enter once, use everywhere) and automates reconciliation. One failed payment due to human error can cost a company far more than a TMS license fee. One compliance violation can be catastrophic.\n\nImproved Cash Visibility: Better visibility means fewer precautionary cash balances. Without a TMS, a treasurer might maintain 20% excess cash as a safety buffer because she can''t see the full position. With a TMS, that can drop to 5%. The difference is millions in cash that can be invested at higher rates, or used for operating expenses.\n\nBetter Investment Returns: With real-time visibility of surplus cash, a treasurer can invest it immediately in higher-yielding instruments (bonds, term deposits) rather than leaving it idle in low-rate call deposits. Even a 1% return improvement on USD 100m in average balances is USD 1m per year.\n\nReduced Borrowing Costs: Better cash forecasting means fewer surprise cash shortfalls and less reliance on expensive overdrafts. The treasury can arrange borrowing in advance at better rates rather than emergency borrowing at premium rates.\n\nRisk Reduction: A TMS that enforces counterparty limits and VaR limits prevents rogue trader scenarios and concentration risk. The cost of a single large counterparty failure or FX blowup far exceeds the cost of a TMS.", "callout": {"label": "Fact", "body": "Quick ROI calculation: A company with USD 500m in average cash balances invests in a TMS at a cost of USD 5m. The system improves investment returns by 1.5% and reduces borrowing costs by 1% (by better forecasting). That''s 1.5% x 500m + 1% x (seasonal borrowing) = USD 7.5m+ per year in benefits, paying for itself in under a year. And that doesn''t include error avoidance, compliance, and risk reduction."}}, {"eyebrow": "CAPSTONE", "heading": "How a TMS Integrates All 10 Steps of This Course", "body": "You''ve now completed 10 steps of Treasury Management. A TMS is where all of them come together. Here''s how.\n\nStep 1: Introduction to Treasury. The TMS''s dashboard is treasury''s command center. It shows the organization''s liquidity position, debt levels, risk metrics. Management sees at a glance whether treasury is meeting its objectives: providing liquidity, managing risk, optimizing returns.\n\nSteps 2.1-2.3: Working Capital Management. The TMS forecasts cash flows (2.3), recommends optimal cash balances (2.1, 2.2), and suggests investment or borrowing decisions. Notional pooling (2.3) is managed in the TMS, with the system calculating net interest on pooled balances.\n\nStep 3.1: Interest Rate Risk. The TMS monitors interest rate exposures from debt and floating-rate investments. It calculates duration and key rate durations. When hedging with interest rate swaps or futures (3.1), the TMS tracks the hedge, marks it to market daily, and calculates the offset against the underlying exposure.\n\nStep 3.2: FX Risk. The TMS aggregates all FX exposures (from operations, investments, and financing). It calculates net long/short positions by currency. When treasury executes FX forwards, money market hedges, or options (3.2), the TMS records these, marks them to market, and reconciles them through CLS or SWIFT settlement (Step 5.1).\n\nSteps 4.1-4.2: Debt and Investment Management. The TMS tracks every debt facility: term, rate, covenants, drawdown schedule. It monitors covenant compliance (Step 4.1) and alerts if a covenant is at risk of breach. For investments, the TMS tracks duration, yield, credit rating, and marks the portfolio to market (Step 4.2). It forecasts maturity ladders and reinvestment decisions.\n\nStep 5.1: Clearing & Settlement Systems. The TMS interfaces with SWIFT and bank APIs to initiate payments and receive settlement instructions. It tracks every trade from deal date through settlement, knows which trades have cleared and which are pending. It reconciles SWIFT confirmations against deal records and alerts to settlement exceptions.\n\nIn a live TMS environment, these ten steps aren''t separate — they''re interwoven. The treasurer enters a bond investment (step 4.2), and the TMS automatically updates the interest rate exposure (step 3.1), the cash position (step 2), the debt-to-equity ratio (step 4.1), and the risk dashboard (step 1). One transaction flows through all systems. That integration is what makes a TMS powerful.", "callout": {"label": "Note", "body": "The final lesson: Treasury is not ten separate functions. Treasury is one unified function orchestrated through systems, policies, and people. A TMS is the tool that makes that orchestration possible. You''ve learned the theory and the tools. A TMS is how professionals apply them in real time."}}], "keyTerms": [{"term": "Treasury Management System (TMS)", "definition": "Software application that automates deal capture, position management, risk analytics, settlement, and reporting for treasury"}, {"term": "Deal capture", "definition": "Entry of a new deal (loan, bond, FX trade, derivative) into the TMS with full term details"}, {"term": "Position management", "definition": "Aggregation of all deals into consolidated positions (cash, FX, debt, investments)"}, {"term": "Value at Risk (VaR)", "definition": "Statistical measure of the maximum loss a portfolio could suffer over a given time horizon at a given confidence level"}, {"term": "Marking to market", "definition": "Revaluing positions daily using current market prices"}, {"term": "Settlement tracking", "definition": "Monitoring deals from inception through clearing to final settlement"}, {"term": "Front office", "definition": "Deal-making and pricing component of a TMS"}, {"term": "Middle office", "definition": "Risk monitoring and control component of a TMS"}, {"term": "Back office", "definition": "Operations, settlement, and reconciliation component of a TMS"}, {"term": "Build vs buy", "definition": "Decision to develop a TMS in-house or purchase a commercial solution"}, {"term": "Integration", "definition": "Connecting a TMS to banks (SWIFT, APIs), ERP systems, and market data providers"}, {"term": "Hard limit", "definition": "Absolute limit enforced by the TMS; transaction is blocked if it exceeds the limit"}, {"term": "Soft limit", "definition": "Warning limit; transaction is allowed but logged and may require approval"}, {"term": "Cash visibility", "definition": "Real-time aggregated view of all bank balances and cash positions across the organization"}, {"term": "Policy enforcement", "definition": "The TMS''s role in enforcing treasury policy through automated rules and controls"}, {"term": "Counterparty exposure", "definition": "Total amount the company owes to or has outstanding with a single counterparty"}, {"term": "Reconciliation", "definition": "Matching transactions in the TMS against bank confirmations to ensure accuracy"}, {"term": "ROI (Return on Investment)", "definition": "Benefit gained from a TMS (error reduction, better returns, risk reduction) measured against its cost"}, {"term": "Data migration", "definition": "Moving historical transaction data from legacy systems into the new TMS"}], "discussionQuestions": ["A company is evaluating whether to build or buy a TMS. What are the key factors that would push you toward buying an off-the-shelf solution vs building one?", "A treasurer discovers that the TMS dashboard is showing a much lower cash position than the company''s accounting ledger. Why might this happen, and what data integrity problems could explain the gap?"], "learningOutcomes": ["Explain what a TMS is and why treasury requires a dedicated system separate from ERP", "Identify and describe the five core functions of a TMS: deal capture, position management, risk analytics, settlement, and reporting", "Explain how a TMS aggregates cash position across multiple banks and currencies, and why this visibility is critical", "Describe the three main connectivity methods for a TMS: SWIFT, host-to-host, and open banking APIs", "Explain the role of front office, middle office, and back office functions within a TMS", "Evaluate a TMS selection using key criteria: scope, scalability, integration, configurability, user adoption, cost, and vendor stability", "Identify common TMS implementation challenges (data migration, integration, user adoption, complexity) and strategies to overcome them", "Explain how a TMS enforces treasury policy through hard limits, soft limits, and approval workflows", "Quantify the ROI of a TMS through error reduction, cash visibility, better investment returns, reduced borrowing costs, and risk reduction", "Demonstrate how a TMS integrates all 10 steps of Treasury Management from working capital through clearing and settlement"]}'::jsonb
where slug = 'treasury-systems'
  and lesson_id = (select id from lessons where slug = 'systems' and course_id = (select id from courses where slug = 'treasury-management'));
